WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:10.700
-OK, welcome back.

00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:15.030
So for those of you who
have come in recently,

00:00:15.030 --> 00:00:19.860
this is our inaugural event of
the next in science program.

00:00:19.860 --> 00:00:23.250
The idea is, at least
from my perspective,

00:00:23.250 --> 00:00:26.790
that a lot of the interesting
new science in emerging areas

00:00:26.790 --> 00:00:29.550
come when we look
across disciplines,

00:00:29.550 --> 00:00:32.159
when there's interdisciplinary
work being done.

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:34.220
And typically early
career scientists

00:00:34.220 --> 00:00:36.680
are the ones that are
leading the charge.

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:42.000
So the philosophy was to bring
in early career scientists

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.240
to talk to a broad
audience, and each other,

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:49.590
for that matter, to help
enlighten us at Harvard

00:00:49.590 --> 00:00:51.470
and the general public
about what might be

00:00:51.470 --> 00:00:53.390
the new frontiers of science.

00:00:53.390 --> 00:00:57.160
So we had two speakers in the
first session, one talking

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:01.000
about living
approaches to building

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:06.140
defensible shorelines and
one about sound communication

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:08.660
between whales and fish.

00:01:08.660 --> 00:01:14.350
And now we're turning to a talk
on the origins of Earth's water

00:01:14.350 --> 00:01:17.870
by Lydia Hallis who is
a Marie Curie research

00:01:17.870 --> 00:01:20.520
fellow at the School
of Geographical

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:23.720
and earth sciences at the
University of Glasgow.

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:27.780
And she did post doctoral work
at the University of Hawaii

00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:35.060
at Manoa and did her doctoral
work at the Natural History

00:01:35.060 --> 00:01:37.040
Museum in London.

00:01:37.040 --> 00:01:40.960
And before the break, we were
talking about the question,

00:01:40.960 --> 00:01:42.340
how do we know that?

00:01:42.340 --> 00:01:46.330
And this is one of these
issues where I frequently

00:01:46.330 --> 00:01:50.650
come across things that I was
taught as a boy in science

00:01:50.650 --> 00:01:53.870
class and I just, sort
of, repeated it verbatim

00:01:53.870 --> 00:01:56.960
as if it's always true, but
not asking the question,

00:01:56.960 --> 00:01:58.950
how do we really
know what it is?

00:01:58.950 --> 00:02:01.620
And so one of the interesting
things for me was I

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:04.060
came across an article
she had published

00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:06.950
on the origins of
water on Earth.

00:02:06.950 --> 00:02:10.009
And I had seen repeated
many, many times that it

00:02:10.009 --> 00:02:11.654
was from comets
smashing into the Earth

00:02:11.654 --> 00:02:13.320
and that's where all
the water came from

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:18.580
and I took that as an article of
faith until I read her article.

00:02:18.580 --> 00:02:24.170
And so I'm fascinated to
actually see this in person

00:02:24.170 --> 00:02:27.762
and get asked
questions so, Lydia.

00:02:27.762 --> 00:02:28.262
-Hi.

00:02:31.790 --> 00:02:33.330
Afternoon, everybody.

00:02:33.330 --> 00:02:36.330
Yes, so now for something
completely different.

00:02:36.330 --> 00:02:39.030
I'm going to be talking about
where Earth's water actually

00:02:39.030 --> 00:02:40.550
came from.

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:42.560
This is not a study
that I've done on my own

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:45.660
in any way, shape or form.

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:49.460
I worked at the University
of Hawaii NASA Astrobiology

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:54.300
Institute for four years before
I came to Glasgow in 2014.

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:58.080
And that institute had been
set up for 10 years prior

00:02:58.080 --> 00:02:59.770
to me even arriving.

00:02:59.770 --> 00:03:03.090
And they had this big
question to answer, where

00:03:03.090 --> 00:03:05.470
did Earth's water come from?

00:03:05.470 --> 00:03:09.310
And, really, it was all
about solar system formation,

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:11.980
and looking at water on
different planetary bodies,

00:03:11.980 --> 00:03:14.070
and trying to
figure out why Earth

00:03:14.070 --> 00:03:19.530
is this really habitable and
nice place for us to live.

00:03:19.530 --> 00:03:24.910
So, the big questions were
did Earth form with water,

00:03:24.910 --> 00:03:26.550
or was water added later?

00:03:26.550 --> 00:03:28.260
So this is the
cometary argument.

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:32.350
Did we get our water
from comets that

00:03:32.350 --> 00:03:34.475
are generated in the
outer solar system

00:03:34.475 --> 00:03:36.870
and come in and collide
with the early Earth?

00:03:36.870 --> 00:03:40.080
Or did Earth form wets
from building blocks

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:42.450
that contained water initially?

00:03:42.450 --> 00:03:46.200
These could have been water
which asteroids, for example.

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:50.020
Where did these building blocks
come from, is another question.

00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:52.310
So, were they are
likely to be water rich?

00:03:52.310 --> 00:03:54.740
Where abouts in the solar
system did they come from?

00:03:54.740 --> 00:03:56.040
The outer solar system?

00:03:56.040 --> 00:03:58.010
The inner solar system?

00:03:58.010 --> 00:04:01.220
Is our material that
the Earth is made from

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:03.540
formed close to
home, or did it come

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:07.040
in from the outer solar system
because of the chaotic nature

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:09.400
of the early solar system?

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:12.400
How much water
does Earth contain?

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:14.670
That seems like a
really simple question

00:04:14.670 --> 00:04:16.250
because it's very
easy for us to add

00:04:16.250 --> 00:04:19.040
up the volume of the
oceans on the surface,

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:21.070
and the volume of the
rivers and the lakes,

00:04:21.070 --> 00:04:23.290
and the amount of water
that's in the atmosphere

00:04:23.290 --> 00:04:26.500
and say this is how
much water is contained.

00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:29.430
It's counter-intuitive
as a non-geologist, which

00:04:29.430 --> 00:04:32.420
I assume a lot of you are,
to think that rocks actually

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:34.300
contain a lot of water.

00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:37.410
But there's more water present
beneath the Earth's surface

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:40.470
by far than there is present
on the surface of the Earth

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:42.330
and in the atmosphere.

00:04:42.330 --> 00:04:44.800
We don't know very much
about how much that

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:49.950
is, there are estimates that
vary between something like six

00:04:49.950 --> 00:04:53.360
oceans worth of water
beneath our feet to,

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:55.890
I think it goes to
about 20 at the moment,

00:04:55.890 --> 00:04:59.670
but it varies all the time.

00:04:59.670 --> 00:05:02.200
And the last question
was, well, now

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:05.070
the last question is does
Earth have more water

00:05:05.070 --> 00:05:06.460
than other terrestrial planets?

00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:08.650
I think when the
Institute was first

00:05:08.650 --> 00:05:11.200
set up that question
would have been

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:14.250
why does Earth have more water
than the other terrestrial

00:05:14.250 --> 00:05:14.750
planets.

00:05:14.750 --> 00:05:18.760
But the more and more we looked
into the amount of water that

00:05:18.760 --> 00:05:20.580
can be present in
the deep Earth,

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:23.600
the more we realized that that
might not actually be true

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:25.630
and that Earth and the
other terrestrial planets

00:05:25.630 --> 00:05:30.230
may have very similar
amounts of water.

00:05:30.230 --> 00:05:32.500
OK, so all of
these questions can

00:05:32.500 --> 00:05:35.270
be answered, or at
least in part answered,

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:39.980
by the study of hydrogen isotope
ratios and water abundancies

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:41.620
in Earth's primitive mantle.

00:05:41.620 --> 00:05:46.590
So this would be a area in the
deep Earth that is chemically

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:50.830
the same as the material that
the Earth formed from 4 and 1/2

00:05:50.830 --> 00:05:51.930
billion years ago.

00:05:51.930 --> 00:05:54.620
Nothing's happened to
it, nothing has changed,

00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:57.710
no surface processes have
affected this material.

00:05:57.710 --> 00:06:01.140
We call it primitive mantle.

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:04.980
So this is where I have to get
into hydrogen isotope ratios.

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:07.910
Please don't fall
asleep, because it

00:06:07.910 --> 00:06:10.320
does get quite geochemical,
but I'll try and, sort of,

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:13.460
reduce most of the geochemistry.

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:16.930
So there are two types of
hydrogen, the two flavors

00:06:16.930 --> 00:06:20.360
of hydrogen. The normal
hydrogen isotope has

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:21.520
an atomic mass of one.

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:24.430
That's normal hydrogen
that's in the air, in water,

00:06:24.430 --> 00:06:26.970
and most of the time on Earth.

00:06:26.970 --> 00:06:30.140
Then there's the
other hydrogen isotope

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:31.660
which we call deuterium.

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:34.360
So the symbol for
it is D. It just

00:06:34.360 --> 00:06:38.060
has an extra neutron
in its atomic nucleus.

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:41.060
So it has an atomic mass of two.

00:06:41.060 --> 00:06:44.360
Comparing the D and H ratio
of different planetary bodies

00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:47.290
can indicate the
origin of these bodies.

00:06:47.290 --> 00:06:49.920
For example, whether they came
from the inner solar system,

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:52.900
or whether they came from
the outer solar system.

00:06:52.900 --> 00:06:55.630
And in very general
terms, we can explain this

00:06:55.630 --> 00:06:58.590
if we look at how the
solar system formed.

00:06:58.590 --> 00:07:01.490
So before the sun
formed, we have what's

00:07:01.490 --> 00:07:02.830
called the molecular cloud.

00:07:02.830 --> 00:07:04.560
And this is all of
the dust and gas

00:07:04.560 --> 00:07:08.270
that later went on to form
the planets and the sun.

00:07:08.270 --> 00:07:11.900
In this molecular cloud there
is water already as a molecule.

00:07:11.900 --> 00:07:14.440
And the water is
very deuterium rich,

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:18.330
so it has a lot of the
heavier hydrogen isotope.

00:07:18.330 --> 00:07:24.130
When the sun forms, because the
inner solar system becomes hot,

00:07:24.130 --> 00:07:28.460
this water interacts with
molecular hydrogen, so hydrogen

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:32.250
gas, H2, which has
a low DH ratio.

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:35.750
So that means it has a lot of
the lighter hydrogen isotope.

00:07:35.750 --> 00:07:38.290
And this interaction
means that the water then

00:07:38.290 --> 00:07:41.970
becomes rich in the
lighter hydrogen isotope,

00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:44.260
it has a low DH ratio.

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:46.320
In the outer solar
system, because it's still

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:52.470
cold in this region of the
outer disk, in this area here,

00:07:52.470 --> 00:07:53.900
you don't get that reaction.

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:56.380
Because it's cold, it's
really cold out there.

00:07:56.380 --> 00:07:59.760
So the reaction either doesn't
happen, or it's very sluggish.

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:02.680
So not much of the water
of the molecular cloud

00:08:02.680 --> 00:08:04.870
will interact with hydrogen gas.

00:08:04.870 --> 00:08:09.290
Therefore, you get the DH
ratio of the molecular cloud

00:08:09.290 --> 00:08:11.560
in the outer solar
system still to this day.

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:15.070
Which means that
right now, in general,

00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:21.440
the closer that you are to the
sun, the lower the DH ratio,

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:24.870
so the more light
hydrogen you have.

00:08:24.870 --> 00:08:27.300
The further out you go,
the more the deuterium

00:08:27.300 --> 00:08:30.270
you have, so the
higher the DH ratio.

00:08:33.940 --> 00:08:37.340
OK, in terms of notation, to
make that a little bit simpler,

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:41.659
we use delta D. So we stop
talking about DH ratios

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:44.380
and we just use
units of delta D.

00:08:44.380 --> 00:08:46.900
To make things simple we
standardize everything

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:49.080
to Earth's ocean water.

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:51.480
So Vienna Standard
Mean Ocean Water there,

00:08:51.480 --> 00:08:55.720
which is VSMOW we call it,
has a delta D value of zero.

00:08:55.720 --> 00:08:58.580
And everything is
compared to ocean water.

00:08:58.580 --> 00:09:01.620
So anything with a
positive delta D value

00:09:01.620 --> 00:09:04.830
is richer in deuterium
than ocean water.

00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:08.100
And anything with a
negative delta D value

00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:11.440
is richer in the lighter
hydrogen isotope.

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:13.220
So it's poorer in deuterium.

00:09:13.220 --> 00:09:15.310
So, for example, on
Earth ice and rocks

00:09:15.310 --> 00:09:17.510
tend to have negative
delta D values

00:09:17.510 --> 00:09:20.080
because they preferentially
incorporate the lighter

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:23.010
hydrogen isotope.

00:09:23.010 --> 00:09:25.140
This gets a little
bit more complicated

00:09:25.140 --> 00:09:30.040
because hydrogen isn't a
normal isotopic system.

00:09:30.040 --> 00:09:32.990
Deuterium has twice the
atomic mass of hydrogen,

00:09:32.990 --> 00:09:36.090
and that doesn't happen in
any other isotopic system.

00:09:36.090 --> 00:09:38.370
It means that the mass
difference between the two

00:09:38.370 --> 00:09:41.800
isotopes is very large, so
you get a very large effect

00:09:41.800 --> 00:09:44.270
when you melt something,
when you freeze something,

00:09:44.270 --> 00:09:46.080
or when you evaporate something.

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:48.760
They separate from
each other very easily.

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:51.290
So it means that when
you freeze something

00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:54.020
you can get a preferential
incorporation of the lighter

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:57.930
hydrogen isotopes, but also
when you evaporate water

00:09:57.930 --> 00:10:00.050
from the oceans
into the atmosphere

00:10:00.050 --> 00:10:03.580
you also get the preferential
incorporation of the lighter

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:04.680
hydrogen isotope.

00:10:04.680 --> 00:10:06.986
Because it's lighter so
it evaporates easier,

00:10:06.986 --> 00:10:08.610
so you get more of
the lighter hydrogen

00:10:08.610 --> 00:10:09.693
isotope in the atmosphere.

00:10:13.780 --> 00:10:16.040
To complicate
matters further, we

00:10:16.040 --> 00:10:19.810
have something called
genes or thermal escape

00:10:19.810 --> 00:10:21.980
in the upper layers
of our atmosphere.

00:10:21.980 --> 00:10:24.370
This happens on all
planetary bodies.

00:10:24.370 --> 00:10:27.440
And what it means is that
because the lighter hydrogen

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:30.940
isotope is only half
the mass of deuterium,

00:10:30.940 --> 00:10:34.130
it takes much less
energy for that atom

00:10:34.130 --> 00:10:36.050
to reach it's escape velocity.

00:10:36.050 --> 00:10:39.270
So when high energy particles
come into the upper atmosphere

00:10:39.270 --> 00:10:42.040
such as solar wind,
cosmic rays, and they

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:45.400
hit one of these atoms, the
lighter hydrogen isotope

00:10:45.400 --> 00:10:48.840
can much easier be blasted
off and lost to space

00:10:48.840 --> 00:10:50.340
than deuterium.

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:52.600
And so what happens
over geological time,

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:54.950
over these 4 and 1/2 billion
years the Earth has been

00:10:54.950 --> 00:10:57.360
around, is that
we preferentially

00:10:57.360 --> 00:11:00.070
lose the hydrogen
isotope and the DH

00:11:00.070 --> 00:11:03.570
ratio will go up over time.

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:07.690
So this is really, really
well demonstrated by Mars.

00:11:07.690 --> 00:11:10.450
So I'm going to move away
from the Earth for a second.

00:11:10.450 --> 00:11:14.650
Mars' atmosphere is very,
very deuterium enriched.

00:11:14.650 --> 00:11:17.140
And the reason for
that is because Earth

00:11:17.140 --> 00:11:19.850
has a magnetic field, a
global magnetic field, that

00:11:19.850 --> 00:11:22.784
protects us from a lot of
the radiation from the sun

00:11:22.784 --> 00:11:25.200
and a lot of the solar wind
stripping that would otherwise

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:26.300
occur.

00:11:26.300 --> 00:11:30.530
Mars did have a global
magnetic field until around 4

00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:35.420
billion years ago, and then the
global magnetic field stopped.

00:11:35.420 --> 00:11:38.140
That's another question
as to why that happened.

00:11:38.140 --> 00:11:40.030
But it disappeared of
four billion years.

00:11:40.030 --> 00:11:42.320
And since then
Mars' atmosphere has

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:44.560
been exposed to the
solar wind, and it's

00:11:44.560 --> 00:11:46.850
been slowly stripped away.

00:11:46.850 --> 00:11:49.420
Deuterium and hydrogen
have been stripped away

00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:50.260
at different rates.

00:11:50.260 --> 00:11:53.180
And so we have this
value of plus 2000

00:11:53.180 --> 00:11:57.830
to plus 8000 in Mars' atmosphere
at the moment because deuterium

00:11:57.830 --> 00:12:01.360
has been left behind and
the lighter hydrogen isotope

00:12:01.360 --> 00:12:03.980
has been preferentially
stripped away.

00:12:03.980 --> 00:12:05.950
Just because Earth
has a magnetic field

00:12:05.950 --> 00:12:07.760
doesn't mean this hasn't
happened on Earth,

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:11.950
it just means the
process isn't so extreme.

00:12:11.950 --> 00:12:15.670
So the bottom line is
changes in the DH ratio

00:12:15.670 --> 00:12:18.070
via atmospheric and
surface processes

00:12:18.070 --> 00:12:20.650
mean we can't rely
on any surface

00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:23.910
water, or any
upper mantle water,

00:12:23.910 --> 00:12:27.470
really, on Earth to give us
the original hydrogen isotope

00:12:27.470 --> 00:12:29.840
ratio of Earth.

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:32.660
We must go deeper
into the mantle.

00:12:32.660 --> 00:12:35.230
So, as I just mentioned,
Earth is complicated

00:12:35.230 --> 00:12:37.970
because we do have
plate tectonics.

00:12:37.970 --> 00:12:41.320
No other body in the solar
system has plate tectonics.

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:43.510
On Mars you have a static crust.

00:12:43.510 --> 00:12:47.440
So the atmosphere and the
mantle are completely separated.

00:12:47.440 --> 00:12:51.250
And if you measure the DH
ratio in a Martian meteorite,

00:12:51.250 --> 00:12:53.180
in water trapped in
a Martian meteorite,

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:57.050
it's low, different to
the atmosphere completely.

00:12:57.050 --> 00:12:59.840
On Earth, because
you've got this mixing

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:02.020
of subducted plates,
you potentially

00:13:02.020 --> 00:13:05.030
have ocean water and
sediment mixing down

00:13:05.030 --> 00:13:08.030
into the upper mantle and
possibly parts of the deeper

00:13:08.030 --> 00:13:09.360
mantle.

00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:13.170
You can't rely on any mantle
material, or any normal rock,

00:13:13.170 --> 00:13:15.370
to give you the
original signature,

00:13:15.370 --> 00:13:19.172
the primitive hydrogen
isotope signature of Earth.

00:13:19.172 --> 00:13:21.380
We have to go even deeper
down than the upper mantle.

00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:28.380
Rock samples from
the deepest areas

00:13:28.380 --> 00:13:30.460
that are exposed
on the surface are

00:13:30.460 --> 00:13:33.420
found in Hawaii,
Iceland, Baffin Island,

00:13:33.420 --> 00:13:36.840
all these hot spot
volcano environments.

00:13:36.840 --> 00:13:39.610
The Galapagos and
the Canary Islands

00:13:39.610 --> 00:13:42.230
are two of the good examples.

00:13:42.230 --> 00:13:45.700
And they come from what
are known as plumes,

00:13:45.700 --> 00:13:47.490
the hot spots on the surface.

00:13:47.490 --> 00:13:51.050
This plume material is thought
to come from the core mantle

00:13:51.050 --> 00:13:51.720
boundary.

00:13:51.720 --> 00:13:54.970
So this is the core
here, the mantle in red,

00:13:54.970 --> 00:13:57.070
and this plume material
comes up all the way

00:13:57.070 --> 00:13:58.670
from the core mantle boundary.

00:13:58.670 --> 00:14:00.570
So that's thousands
of kilometers.

00:14:00.570 --> 00:14:04.380
This material comes up to the
surface, is erupted as lava,

00:14:04.380 --> 00:14:09.150
solidifies into rock, and
hopefully traps its chemistry,

00:14:09.150 --> 00:14:11.510
the chemistry from down
here, at this surface for us

00:14:11.510 --> 00:14:13.510
to go and sample and pick
up and have a look at.

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:19.000
So that is what we aim to do.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:20.670
The first samples
that we looked up

00:14:20.670 --> 00:14:25.480
with from Baffin Island, a
place called Padloping Island.

00:14:25.480 --> 00:14:26.940
So this is Padloping
Island, it's

00:14:26.940 --> 00:14:33.010
only a few kilometers across,
the cliff edges all along here.

00:14:33.010 --> 00:14:35.970
The samples were
collected in 1985

00:14:35.970 --> 00:14:41.000
by Professor Don Francis at
McGill University in Montreal.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:45.170
And they were collected from
this Northern area here.

00:14:45.170 --> 00:14:46.670
When he collected
the samples he had

00:14:46.670 --> 00:14:50.279
no idea how geochemically
special they were,

00:14:50.279 --> 00:14:51.820
but in the interim
years they've been

00:14:51.820 --> 00:14:53.820
really intensively studied.

00:14:53.820 --> 00:14:55.380
And it's found that
they are actually

00:14:55.380 --> 00:14:58.220
quite unique sample set.

00:14:58.220 --> 00:15:02.370
For example, they contain the
highest helium isotope ratios

00:15:02.370 --> 00:15:05.290
ever measured in
a sample on Earth.

00:15:05.290 --> 00:15:09.290
I'm not going to go into
helium isotopic ratios.

00:15:09.290 --> 00:15:12.680
But, basically, if you have
a high helium isotope ratio,

00:15:12.680 --> 00:15:16.630
it means that your sample
has been undegassed,

00:15:16.630 --> 00:15:20.100
has been undisturbed
since the formation

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:24.060
or the beginning of the Earth.

00:15:24.060 --> 00:15:30.030
Similarly we have
lead isotopes that

00:15:30.030 --> 00:15:33.365
show an ancient
undisturbed mantle source.

00:15:33.365 --> 00:15:36.480
So we know that this
source of this plume

00:15:36.480 --> 00:15:40.140
has been untouched
by any mantle mixing,

00:15:40.140 --> 00:15:42.520
by any mixing of
different sources down

00:15:42.520 --> 00:15:48.050
in the deep mantle, for
4.55 to 4.45 billion years.

00:15:48.050 --> 00:15:50.960
So that's almost the
age of the Earth.

00:15:50.960 --> 00:15:53.430
It's around about the
age that the moon formed

00:15:53.430 --> 00:15:56.880
on the Earth, the giant impact.

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:59.530
The other special thing about
these Padloping Island samples

00:15:59.530 --> 00:16:03.630
is, because we're trying to
measure hydrogen inside a rock,

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:06.380
we want the hydrogen
to still be in there.

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:09.370
We don't want the lava to
erupt, and degas, and lose

00:16:09.370 --> 00:16:11.980
lots of steam as it erupts.

00:16:11.980 --> 00:16:14.680
So it needs to be
erupted under pressure.

00:16:14.680 --> 00:16:18.630
So these rocks were erupted
around about 60,000 years ago

00:16:18.630 --> 00:16:22.920
under water, under seawater,
deep down under the sea.

00:16:22.920 --> 00:16:24.740
So they erupted
under pressure, which

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:28.430
means that the gases that are
in those rocks can't escape.

00:16:28.430 --> 00:16:30.620
They're trapped.

00:16:30.620 --> 00:16:33.540
The things we actually
measured in the samples

00:16:33.540 --> 00:16:35.580
were glassy melt inclusions.

00:16:35.580 --> 00:16:41.050
So these are electron microscope
images of some of the samples.

00:16:41.050 --> 00:16:44.290
These dark gray crystals you can
see here are olivine crystals.

00:16:44.290 --> 00:16:47.770
That's a really common
mineral in lots of types

00:16:47.770 --> 00:16:50.150
of rock in the ocean crust.

00:16:50.150 --> 00:16:53.177
Generally on the Earth olivine
is a very common mineral.

00:16:53.177 --> 00:16:55.260
But, the great thing about
olivine is that it does

00:16:55.260 --> 00:16:58.170
tend to trap these, what
are called, melt inclusions.

00:16:58.170 --> 00:17:02.530
They're basically little,
tiny pockets of lava

00:17:02.530 --> 00:17:05.700
that gets trapped as
the crystals forming

00:17:05.700 --> 00:17:08.990
and the composition of
that lava is then trapped

00:17:08.990 --> 00:17:11.210
as it was before
crystallization.

00:17:11.210 --> 00:17:15.290
So you've got a sample
there of the melt

00:17:15.290 --> 00:17:18.521
as it came from the deep mantle.

00:17:18.521 --> 00:17:20.270
The great thing about
the olivine crystal,

00:17:20.270 --> 00:17:22.589
as well, is, as I
mentioned, these samples

00:17:22.589 --> 00:17:25.260
have been on the surface
for 60,000 years.

00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:28.870
Rain water, ice, at
Baffin Island sea water,

00:17:28.870 --> 00:17:31.580
can get to that
glass if it's not

00:17:31.580 --> 00:17:33.190
protected by these crystals.

00:17:33.190 --> 00:17:35.970
But the crystals are
protecting the glass.

00:17:35.970 --> 00:17:39.750
And it's very easy to see
whether an olivine crystal has

00:17:39.750 --> 00:17:43.060
been weathered to something
like a clay, in which case

00:17:43.060 --> 00:17:43.960
we would avoid it.

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:46.100
These are pristine
olivine samples

00:17:46.100 --> 00:17:48.070
that haven't been
weathered at all,

00:17:48.070 --> 00:17:51.360
so we know that rainwater
hasn't got into the glass

00:17:51.360 --> 00:17:54.910
and contaminated what
we're trying to look for.

00:17:54.910 --> 00:17:59.140
We also looked at
samples from Iceland,

00:17:59.140 --> 00:18:01.640
very similar type of samples.

00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:04.220
Again, the high
helium isotope ratios

00:18:04.220 --> 00:18:06.010
really shows that
we're looking at rocks

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:12.050
that are from a primitive and
isolated source from subductive

00:18:12.050 --> 00:18:14.970
mixing down in the deep mantle.

00:18:14.970 --> 00:18:17.060
These samples were
erupted subglacially,

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:19.700
but essentially that's
the same as [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:19.700 --> 00:18:22.952
They're under pressure, so it
stops the gas from escaping.

00:18:22.952 --> 00:18:24.910
Again, we're looking at
glassy melt inclusions,

00:18:24.910 --> 00:18:28.000
so these are some of
the inclusions in here.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:32.910
If you've noticed the scale on
here, that's 40 microns there.

00:18:32.910 --> 00:18:38.530
So that's about a 35 micron
width melt inclusion.

00:18:38.530 --> 00:18:41.829
That's about a fifth the
width of a human hair,

00:18:41.829 --> 00:18:43.120
and that's one of the big ones.

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:45.960
Because that's why I've taken an
image of it, that's a good one.

00:18:45.960 --> 00:18:49.200
So the others are much
smaller than that.

00:18:49.200 --> 00:18:51.220
They're really, really
difficult measurements

00:18:51.220 --> 00:18:55.800
to make, because that
isn't a water glob

00:18:55.800 --> 00:19:00.350
inside, it isn't a liquid
bit of water, it's glass.

00:19:00.350 --> 00:19:03.879
It's only got parts per million
of water in the actual glass

00:19:03.879 --> 00:19:05.420
and we're looking
at something that's

00:19:05.420 --> 00:19:08.100
less than 40 microns across.

00:19:08.100 --> 00:19:10.190
So the measurements are
really, really difficult.

00:19:10.190 --> 00:19:13.910
Not only that, but the
samples have to be polished,

00:19:13.910 --> 00:19:16.080
they have to be prepared.

00:19:16.080 --> 00:19:18.100
So how do you do that
without using water,

00:19:18.100 --> 00:19:21.790
without using any kind of resin
that doesn't contain hydrogen,

00:19:21.790 --> 00:19:24.410
without exposing them
to the atmosphere,

00:19:24.410 --> 00:19:27.830
or touching them with your
fingers, or breathing on them?

00:19:27.830 --> 00:19:30.450
It took years for us to
perfect the methodology

00:19:30.450 --> 00:19:34.590
to be able to make
these measurements.

00:19:34.590 --> 00:19:36.580
It helps if you've
got a big machine.

00:19:36.580 --> 00:19:39.780
Which in Hawaii
we have something

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:43.180
called the Cameca 1280
ims ion-microprobe.

00:19:43.180 --> 00:19:43.980
It's this thing.

00:19:43.980 --> 00:19:46.535
It's the size of a
big room like this.

00:19:46.535 --> 00:19:50.010
It makes a variation
of different noises.

00:19:50.010 --> 00:19:54.930
And there are three people that
permanently run this thing.

00:19:54.930 --> 00:19:58.880
It has a very high vacuum
sample chamber here which

00:19:58.880 --> 00:20:00.920
we put the samples in.

00:20:00.920 --> 00:20:03.520
They're stored in a
vacuum oven at 60 degrees

00:20:03.520 --> 00:20:05.280
C to stop hydrogen
getting anywhere

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:06.970
near the surface of the sample.

00:20:06.970 --> 00:20:09.140
We then put them at
very high vacuum in here

00:20:09.140 --> 00:20:11.440
and we bombard them
with cesium ions.

00:20:11.440 --> 00:20:15.740
So a beam of charged
particles hits the surface

00:20:15.740 --> 00:20:21.300
and makes these little pits over
what were the melt inclusions.

00:20:21.300 --> 00:20:23.940
The pits are about one
micron depth in size,

00:20:23.940 --> 00:20:27.020
so you're not really
destroying much of the sample.

00:20:27.020 --> 00:20:30.250
And you make an aerosol
which then goes through here

00:20:30.250 --> 00:20:32.470
into the mass
spectrometer and tells you

00:20:32.470 --> 00:20:35.950
how much hydrogen you've got
versus how much deuterium

00:20:35.950 --> 00:20:38.140
you have.

00:20:38.140 --> 00:20:41.660
I should mention we also
measured oxygen isotopes just

00:20:41.660 --> 00:20:44.080
to be able to tell
whether we did have

00:20:44.080 --> 00:20:47.540
any contamination from things
like rainwater, from things

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:50.190
like mixing as the samples
came up through the crust,

00:20:50.190 --> 00:20:54.410
did they dissolve any
kind of crystal rock

00:20:54.410 --> 00:20:56.680
into the sample which would
contaminate our hydrogen

00:20:56.680 --> 00:20:57.360
signature.

00:20:57.360 --> 00:20:59.300
If you imagine you
have some lava that

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:01.844
dissolves a lot of sediment
that's very water rich,

00:21:01.844 --> 00:21:03.260
you don't want
that in your sample

00:21:03.260 --> 00:21:06.610
because it's going to
contaminate the results.

00:21:06.610 --> 00:21:08.560
So if I start with
this graph, actually,

00:21:08.560 --> 00:21:12.700
you can see our Icelandic
samples the points are in gray,

00:21:12.700 --> 00:21:14.780
the Baffin Island
samples are in red,

00:21:14.780 --> 00:21:18.020
and we compare them to
some previous Hawaiian data

00:21:18.020 --> 00:21:20.880
which is this green point here.

00:21:20.880 --> 00:21:24.690
Two of the Icelandic samples
showed altered oceanic crust

00:21:24.690 --> 00:21:25.480
contaminant.

00:21:25.480 --> 00:21:29.850
So immediately we
discounted these samples.

00:21:29.850 --> 00:21:33.600
So we've got delta D. Again,
Vienna Standard Mean Ocean

00:21:33.600 --> 00:21:35.630
Water is zero,
anything above that

00:21:35.630 --> 00:21:38.730
is deuterium rich
compared to ocean water,

00:21:38.730 --> 00:21:43.450
anything below is more rich in
the lighter hydrogen isotope.

00:21:43.450 --> 00:21:47.620
All our samples, apart from
these Icelandic samples

00:21:47.620 --> 00:21:51.170
which are contaminated, plotted
below Vienna Standard Mean

00:21:51.170 --> 00:21:52.460
Ocean line.

00:21:52.460 --> 00:21:55.810
That's not surprising because,
as I had mentioned, normal rock

00:21:55.810 --> 00:21:59.390
samples, they have a
negative value anyway.

00:21:59.390 --> 00:22:02.570
But this is the region of
the normal rock samples, what

00:22:02.570 --> 00:22:06.530
we call MORB, it means
Mid-Ocean Ridge Basalt. So, it's

00:22:06.530 --> 00:22:13.150
a typical sample of a
typical mantle basalt.

00:22:13.150 --> 00:22:15.110
They plot in this very
narrow region here,

00:22:15.110 --> 00:22:18.680
in this orange rectangle,
at around about minus 55

00:22:18.680 --> 00:22:20.250
to minus 65.

00:22:20.250 --> 00:22:22.150
None of our Baffin
Island samples,

00:22:22.150 --> 00:22:26.510
and this one Icelandic sample,
they don't plot in that region.

00:22:26.510 --> 00:22:29.120
So they're not
typical mantle samples

00:22:29.120 --> 00:22:32.700
according to the DH ratio.

00:22:32.700 --> 00:22:37.900
I've just plotted along
with water content here.

00:22:37.900 --> 00:22:40.250
Water content is interesting,
because we're also

00:22:40.250 --> 00:22:41.940
looking to see how
much water there

00:22:41.940 --> 00:22:45.220
is in the mantle in general.

00:22:45.220 --> 00:22:47.150
The MORB basalts
have a variation,

00:22:47.150 --> 00:22:49.650
so normal basalts have a
variation of water content.

00:22:49.650 --> 00:22:53.160
And it goes up to about
0.1 of a weight percent,

00:22:53.160 --> 00:22:55.710
so 0.1 percent,
really, of the rock

00:22:55.710 --> 00:23:01.530
will be water in the most water
rich normal mantle basalts.

00:23:01.530 --> 00:23:08.130
Our samples extend much further
in terms of water content

00:23:08.130 --> 00:23:11.600
and have much lower DH ratios.

00:23:11.600 --> 00:23:13.630
So this delta D value
here, the lowest

00:23:13.630 --> 00:23:18.490
that we measured in a Baffin
Island sample, was minus 218.

00:23:18.490 --> 00:23:23.490
That's about-- the
lowest value before that

00:23:23.490 --> 00:23:28.790
was these Hawaiian samples at,
I think this one is minus 165.

00:23:28.790 --> 00:23:31.490
So we've gone quite a bit
lower than previous samples,

00:23:31.490 --> 00:23:35.390
and these samples are even
much lower than normal samples.

00:23:35.390 --> 00:23:39.990
So we can definitely say there's
a source in the deep mantle

00:23:39.990 --> 00:23:42.170
that has a lot more of
the lighter hydrogen

00:23:42.170 --> 00:23:47.360
isotope than Vienna
Standard Mean Ocean Water.

00:23:47.360 --> 00:23:49.640
In addition, it's
got more water.

00:23:49.640 --> 00:23:50.730
So why would that be?

00:23:50.730 --> 00:23:54.357
Well, we came up with
this hypothetical source.

00:23:54.357 --> 00:23:56.190
As I mentioned at the
beginning of the talk,

00:23:56.190 --> 00:24:00.970
the sun and normal
molecular hydrogen

00:24:00.970 --> 00:24:04.260
have a lot of the
lighter hydrogen isotope.

00:24:04.260 --> 00:24:06.530
They have a very
negative delta D value.

00:24:06.530 --> 00:24:12.250
It's actually at minus 870,
so it's somewhere down here.

00:24:12.250 --> 00:24:14.620
So we use that as
our theoretical sort

00:24:14.620 --> 00:24:19.640
of end member for our
theoretical deep mantle source.

00:24:19.640 --> 00:24:23.210
And we use the water content
of around about 1 weight

00:24:23.210 --> 00:24:24.420
percent water.

00:24:24.420 --> 00:24:28.580
Because, based on the Hawaiian
lavas, and previous researchers

00:24:28.580 --> 00:24:31.280
have determined
that these samples,

00:24:31.280 --> 00:24:36.070
their source regions had around
about one weight percent water.

00:24:36.070 --> 00:24:39.050
So that source plots
somewhere over here.

00:24:39.050 --> 00:24:41.330
None of our material
in the glassy melt

00:24:41.330 --> 00:24:44.660
inclusions plots anywhere
near this theoretical,

00:24:44.660 --> 00:24:46.560
what we call the
protosolar source, so

00:24:46.560 --> 00:24:48.520
a very primitive source.

00:24:48.520 --> 00:24:52.770
We get around, at the
lowest values, a 20% value.

00:24:52.770 --> 00:24:57.000
So it's 20% this
protosolar source, and 80%

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:59.870
this normal MORB mantle source.

00:24:59.870 --> 00:25:02.750
You would expect that
the diagram I showed you

00:25:02.750 --> 00:25:05.740
earlier on with the core
mantle boundary and the plume

00:25:05.740 --> 00:25:08.870
coming up through thousands
of kilometers of mantle,

00:25:08.870 --> 00:25:12.240
you would not expect that
that plume hadn't interacted

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:14.240
in any way with all
of the mantle material

00:25:14.240 --> 00:25:15.680
that it was coming through.

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:18.360
It's obviously
interacted quite a bit.

00:25:18.360 --> 00:25:21.150
But we do see a 20%
signature of something

00:25:21.150 --> 00:25:23.160
that's potentially
quite rare and that

00:25:23.160 --> 00:25:26.120
doesn't exist elsewhere on the
surface of the Earth, something

00:25:26.120 --> 00:25:29.490
that we don't have
pure samples of.

00:25:29.490 --> 00:25:32.160
-What was that 20% one for?

00:25:32.160 --> 00:25:33.100
That one?

00:25:33.100 --> 00:25:34.230
-This one?

00:25:34.230 --> 00:25:40.290
So this is 20% the theoretical
protosolar source here.

00:25:40.290 --> 00:25:42.650
-And where did it
come from again?

00:25:42.650 --> 00:25:43.150
You said it.

00:25:43.150 --> 00:25:44.620
-Oh, this is from Baffin Island.

00:25:44.620 --> 00:25:46.540
So the red samples are
from Baffin Island,

00:25:46.540 --> 00:25:48.480
and the gray are from Iceland.

00:25:48.480 --> 00:25:51.260
So it looks as though,
also, the Icelandic samples

00:25:51.260 --> 00:25:54.310
may have been more
degassed, because they

00:25:54.310 --> 00:25:56.360
contain less water.

00:25:56.360 --> 00:26:00.840
So glacial eruption probably
didn't pressurize quite as much

00:26:00.840 --> 00:26:03.500
as the subaqueous eruptions.

00:26:03.500 --> 00:26:05.750
I'm sure there's been
degassing in all of them,

00:26:05.750 --> 00:26:07.290
but it's the amount
of degassing.

00:26:07.290 --> 00:26:09.760
Here you can see they're
quite water poor compared

00:26:09.760 --> 00:26:11.999
to the Baffin Island samples.

00:26:11.999 --> 00:26:14.290
So maybe they just weren't
under quite enough pressure.

00:26:18.260 --> 00:26:21.250
In terms of oxygen
isotopes, something

00:26:21.250 --> 00:26:23.620
that we found that we
didn't expect to find

00:26:23.620 --> 00:26:26.820
was there's a correlation
between the DH ratio,

00:26:26.820 --> 00:26:30.700
the delta D values here, and
the oxygen isotope ratio.

00:26:30.700 --> 00:26:34.970
And it seems that--
this is delta 18 O,

00:26:34.970 --> 00:26:39.990
it just means
oxygen isotope of 18

00:26:39.990 --> 00:26:42.670
over an oxygen isotope
of atomic mass 16.

00:26:42.670 --> 00:26:45.380
That's the ratio there.

00:26:45.380 --> 00:26:48.800
What we see is an enrichment
in the lighter hydrogen

00:26:48.800 --> 00:26:51.730
isotopes, so a more
negative delta D value,

00:26:51.730 --> 00:26:56.120
corresponds with a lower delta
18 O value, so an enrichment

00:26:56.120 --> 00:26:59.660
in the lighter oxygen isotope.

00:26:59.660 --> 00:27:02.320
We don't really
know why this is,

00:27:02.320 --> 00:27:08.320
but protosolar things
like the solar wind

00:27:08.320 --> 00:27:11.380
are very rich in
oxygen 16 compared

00:27:11.380 --> 00:27:13.682
to sources on the Earth.

00:27:13.682 --> 00:27:15.640
So this is hinting that
there's something there

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:17.860
that we haven't
quite understood yet.

00:27:23.020 --> 00:27:25.180
In terms of the source
of Earth's water,

00:27:25.180 --> 00:27:26.040
what does this mean?

00:27:26.040 --> 00:27:30.180
We've got a low DH ratio,
we've got lots of the lighter

00:27:30.180 --> 00:27:32.050
hydrogen isotope.

00:27:32.050 --> 00:27:35.780
What bodies in the solar system
have a similar DH ration?

00:27:35.780 --> 00:27:37.920
Well, the, sort of, front
runner at the moment

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:40.530
is the C type asteroids.

00:27:40.530 --> 00:27:42.840
These asteroids are
thought to be the parent

00:27:42.840 --> 00:27:45.730
body for what are known as
the carbonaceous chondrite

00:27:45.730 --> 00:27:46.750
meteorites.

00:27:46.750 --> 00:27:49.300
They're quite a common
meteorite group on Earth,

00:27:49.300 --> 00:27:51.660
they're known to
contain a lot of water.

00:27:51.660 --> 00:27:54.520
Some of them are very clay
rich and they contain up

00:27:54.520 --> 00:27:56.300
to 10 weight percent water.

00:27:56.300 --> 00:27:58.910
So there's no
problem in us forming

00:27:58.910 --> 00:28:01.950
the Earth from 100%
carbonaceous chondrites

00:28:01.950 --> 00:28:03.170
and having enough water.

00:28:03.170 --> 00:28:05.950
In fact, we'd have way too much.

00:28:05.950 --> 00:28:08.660
But it's very unlikely
that the Earth

00:28:08.660 --> 00:28:11.880
formed from 100% these
carbonaceous chondrites.

00:28:11.880 --> 00:28:15.670
It's more likely that it was
a mixture of different things.

00:28:15.670 --> 00:28:19.630
In terms of the DH
ratio, that works.

00:28:19.630 --> 00:28:23.170
These C values here that
you see in the orange lines,

00:28:23.170 --> 00:28:25.870
this is DH ratio
here, you can see

00:28:25.870 --> 00:28:29.100
they plot below Vienna Standard
Mean Ocean Water, which

00:28:29.100 --> 00:28:31.960
is this orange Earth line.

00:28:31.960 --> 00:28:36.200
Minus 218, which is our
lowest Baffin Island sample,

00:28:36.200 --> 00:28:37.570
is around about here.

00:28:37.570 --> 00:28:39.970
So they do correspond
to that lower value.

00:28:39.970 --> 00:28:41.980
Some of them plot much lower.

00:28:41.980 --> 00:28:43.560
This is that protosolar
source that I

00:28:43.560 --> 00:28:47.420
was talking about at minus 870.

00:28:47.420 --> 00:28:48.790
We can see the comets up here.

00:28:48.790 --> 00:28:52.710
Really, they don't have anything
to do with these values.

00:28:52.710 --> 00:28:57.330
You cannot get all of Earth's
water from cometary origins

00:28:57.330 --> 00:29:00.640
and have the right DH ratios,
even just for the ocean water,

00:29:00.640 --> 00:29:03.320
and let alone for what we
found in the deep mantle.

00:29:03.320 --> 00:29:06.000
It doesn't work.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:10.330
Another facet of evidence
that's recently been discovered

00:29:10.330 --> 00:29:12.850
is from the eucrite meteorites.

00:29:12.850 --> 00:29:14.690
These are meteorites
that are thought

00:29:14.690 --> 00:29:17.260
to be from the
asteroid Vesta, which

00:29:17.260 --> 00:29:20.070
is present in the main
asteroid belt at the moment.

00:29:20.070 --> 00:29:22.050
It's still there, we
sent a mission to it,

00:29:22.050 --> 00:29:23.070
we had a look at it.

00:29:23.070 --> 00:29:25.390
And we said we've got
these meteorites on Earth,

00:29:25.390 --> 00:29:28.770
we've got these spectra from
a remote sensing orbiter,

00:29:28.770 --> 00:29:31.110
and it looks like they're
made of the same stuff.

00:29:31.110 --> 00:29:33.370
So that was a really
successful mission in saying,

00:29:33.370 --> 00:29:36.510
Yes, we definitely got
pieces of Vesta on Earth

00:29:36.510 --> 00:29:38.740
and they're known as
the eucrite meteorites.

00:29:38.740 --> 00:29:42.190
The interesting thing is
they have the same DH ratio

00:29:42.190 --> 00:29:44.320
as the carbonaceous chondrites.

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:47.325
And so it was said
that the eucrites

00:29:47.325 --> 00:29:50.200
are formed from the
carbonaceous chondrites.

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:53.420
Now Vesta is interesting because
it's not any normal asteroid.

00:29:53.420 --> 00:29:56.300
It's actually, we
think, a remnant

00:29:56.300 --> 00:29:59.900
planetesimal from the
beginning of the solar system.

00:29:59.900 --> 00:30:02.330
So in the early part
of the solar system

00:30:02.330 --> 00:30:04.470
we have smaller
planets that formed

00:30:04.470 --> 00:30:07.200
into larger and larger planets
by hitting into each other,

00:30:07.200 --> 00:30:08.960
colliding, destroying
each other,

00:30:08.960 --> 00:30:11.380
and eventually we end up
with the four rocky planets

00:30:11.380 --> 00:30:13.060
that we have today.

00:30:13.060 --> 00:30:15.200
There were hundreds
of planetesimals,

00:30:15.200 --> 00:30:17.080
and there is now
one that we know

00:30:17.080 --> 00:30:21.260
of that's left that didn't get
destroyed, and that's Vesta.

00:30:21.260 --> 00:30:24.647
It formed only 20 million
years after the formation

00:30:24.647 --> 00:30:26.730
of the solar system-- that
sounds like a long time

00:30:26.730 --> 00:30:29.070
to a non-geologist,
but it really isn't.

00:30:29.070 --> 00:30:31.050
It's a blink of an eye.

00:30:31.050 --> 00:30:34.080
These are some of the oldest
meteorites that we know of,

00:30:34.080 --> 00:30:38.880
and they kind of could
be the intermediate stage

00:30:38.880 --> 00:30:41.520
between these
carbonaceous chondrites

00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:45.320
and the terrestrial planets
like Mars, Earth, Mercury,

00:30:45.320 --> 00:30:47.190
and Venus.

00:30:47.190 --> 00:30:50.100
So this is a really popular
theory at the moment.

00:30:50.100 --> 00:30:53.210
The problem is it
doesn't really work

00:30:53.210 --> 00:30:58.550
because based on models
of solar system formation,

00:30:58.550 --> 00:31:01.640
the carbonaceous chondrites were
nowhere near where Earth was

00:31:01.640 --> 00:31:04.750
forming when it was forming.

00:31:04.750 --> 00:31:08.340
This is a diagram
from a 2011 paper

00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:12.040
that looked at giant
planet migration.

00:31:12.040 --> 00:31:14.630
So these are the giant planets,
the black circles here.

00:31:14.630 --> 00:31:19.220
You've got Jupiter the biggest
and the other three behind it.

00:31:19.220 --> 00:31:21.600
And you can see
that Jupiter moves

00:31:21.600 --> 00:31:25.140
in towards the inner solar
system after about four

00:31:25.140 --> 00:31:27.790
million years after the
solar system formed.

00:31:27.790 --> 00:31:30.840
Jupiter moves in, Saturn follows
a little bit, the other two

00:31:30.840 --> 00:31:32.310
kind of stay where they are.

00:31:32.310 --> 00:31:35.170
And what happens in the
inner solar system where

00:31:35.170 --> 00:31:38.600
the rocky planets are forming
is you get this huge sort

00:31:38.600 --> 00:31:41.130
of chaotic environment.

00:31:41.130 --> 00:31:42.890
Jupiter squashes
everything together

00:31:42.890 --> 00:31:45.500
and everything goes crazy.

00:31:45.500 --> 00:31:47.500
Saturn comes in and
then eventually they

00:31:47.500 --> 00:31:49.910
move back out to
their current orbits

00:31:49.910 --> 00:31:52.570
and you form the
four rocky planets.

00:31:52.570 --> 00:31:54.720
The problem with
this diagram is that

00:31:54.720 --> 00:31:58.310
the carbonaceous chondrites
are the blue dots.

00:31:58.310 --> 00:32:00.890
They formed in the
outer solar system.

00:32:00.890 --> 00:32:04.350
The red dots, which here seem
to be the material that make up

00:32:04.350 --> 00:32:05.900
the terrestrial
planets, are what's

00:32:05.900 --> 00:32:07.930
known as the
ordinary chondrites,

00:32:07.930 --> 00:32:10.140
and they are a very
common meteorite.

00:32:10.140 --> 00:32:11.660
They fall to Earth all the time.

00:32:11.660 --> 00:32:14.200
If any of you remember
the meteor that

00:32:14.200 --> 00:32:17.249
fell over Russia that
landed in the lake,

00:32:17.249 --> 00:32:18.540
that was an ordinary chondrite.

00:32:18.540 --> 00:32:20.800
And everyone got really excited
and then found it, oh, it's

00:32:20.800 --> 00:32:21.716
an ordinary chondrite.

00:32:24.650 --> 00:32:26.940
So, they're common
because they are

00:32:26.940 --> 00:32:28.880
present in the
inner solar system.

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:31.730
The problem is they don't
have the right DH ratio,

00:32:31.730 --> 00:32:34.010
they have a very high DH ratio.

00:32:34.010 --> 00:32:36.940
They contain a lot of deuterium.

00:32:36.940 --> 00:32:39.400
You can see there are
some blue spots in there,

00:32:39.400 --> 00:32:42.400
so there are some
carbonaceous chondrites,

00:32:42.400 --> 00:32:44.460
but calculations
show that this is not

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:47.840
anywhere near enough to produce
either the right hydrogen

00:32:47.840 --> 00:32:51.040
isotope ratios that will
be low enough for Earth,

00:32:51.040 --> 00:32:52.910
or the amount of
water that we think

00:32:52.910 --> 00:32:57.740
is present even on the surface,
even for the lowest estimates.

00:32:57.740 --> 00:32:59.138
So there's a problem here.

00:33:02.100 --> 00:33:04.890
So people started to look
elsewhere and say, OK,

00:33:04.890 --> 00:33:07.690
well what other mechanisms
can we think of.

00:33:07.690 --> 00:33:12.330
So in 2015 a group at Scripps
actually thought, well,

00:33:12.330 --> 00:33:15.850
what about if we just say
we've just got some dust,

00:33:15.850 --> 00:33:18.180
one astronomical
unit from the sun.

00:33:18.180 --> 00:33:20.070
And there's water
in the cloud, we

00:33:20.070 --> 00:33:22.240
know there's water in
the molecular cloud.

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:25.650
How much water will
stick to the dust

00:33:25.650 --> 00:33:28.380
particles, or the
olivine grains,

00:33:28.380 --> 00:33:29.830
at certain temperatures?

00:33:29.830 --> 00:33:31.730
Because it is based
on this assumption

00:33:31.730 --> 00:33:34.900
that in a hot environment you
can't stick water to anything

00:33:34.900 --> 00:33:36.870
because it is present as gas.

00:33:36.870 --> 00:33:38.390
That's not true, it turns out.

00:33:38.390 --> 00:33:42.440
And water molecules will
stick to dust particles

00:33:42.440 --> 00:33:44.400
at up to 900 Kelvin.

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:47.105
So that's, actually,
hotter, we think,

00:33:47.105 --> 00:33:52.080
than the temperature at one
AU when the Earth was forming.

00:33:52.080 --> 00:33:54.210
Not only that, but if
there's a lot of water

00:33:54.210 --> 00:33:58.240
present and you've got
something like an olivine grain,

00:33:58.240 --> 00:34:01.050
it will start to change
to clay material.

00:34:01.050 --> 00:34:04.010
It will start to alter in this
very water rich environment.

00:34:04.010 --> 00:34:07.140
So you get more water
coming in and coming in.

00:34:07.140 --> 00:34:10.110
So, the bottom line of
that is that the entirety

00:34:10.110 --> 00:34:14.110
of Earth's water can actually
be delivered during accretion.

00:34:14.110 --> 00:34:18.659
You don't need any addition
of water from elsewhere.

00:34:18.659 --> 00:34:21.100
Not only will it be
delivered during accretion,

00:34:21.100 --> 00:34:23.340
during the formation of
Earth, but it can actually

00:34:23.340 --> 00:34:25.320
stick around as well.

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:27.520
You form Earth
and it's very hot.

00:34:27.520 --> 00:34:28.449
You have no crust.

00:34:28.449 --> 00:34:30.780
You've got this lava world.

00:34:30.780 --> 00:34:34.120
But that's only the surface,
most of the water is inside.

00:34:34.120 --> 00:34:38.480
So for a water molecule to
get thousands of kilometers

00:34:38.480 --> 00:34:42.780
up in the short time period that
it takes for Earth to solidify

00:34:42.780 --> 00:34:45.370
at the surface is
actually very difficult.

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:47.130
So the argument here
is that yes, you

00:34:47.130 --> 00:34:49.369
will lose a lot of water
because the Earth's hot,

00:34:49.369 --> 00:34:51.020
but you're not going
to lose all of it

00:34:51.020 --> 00:34:52.985
because there was lots
and lots of it around.

00:34:56.510 --> 00:34:58.190
The last slide, what next.

00:34:58.190 --> 00:35:00.480
Well, I mentioned
the oxygen isotopes

00:35:00.480 --> 00:35:04.810
and when I saw the correlation
that kind of suggested

00:35:04.810 --> 00:35:09.690
that the oxygen 16 was very
rich in the samples we measured,

00:35:09.690 --> 00:35:11.190
I was kicking myself
because I only

00:35:11.190 --> 00:35:16.000
measured two isotopes of oxygen.
I didn't measure oxygen 17,

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:18.830
and oxygen 17 is
the important one

00:35:18.830 --> 00:35:23.980
for determining what body each
type of meteorite came from.

00:35:23.980 --> 00:35:27.500
So this is a very complicated
graph, but basically anything

00:35:27.500 --> 00:35:29.620
that is from Earth
at the moment plots

00:35:29.620 --> 00:35:32.986
along this dashed line, the
terrestrial fractionation line.

00:35:32.986 --> 00:35:35.110
Anything that is not from
Earth will plot elsewhere

00:35:35.110 --> 00:35:38.180
in these ellipses, for
the chondritic meteorites,

00:35:38.180 --> 00:35:42.120
this tiny ellipse here for
the Martian meteorites.

00:35:42.120 --> 00:35:47.730
Our sample suggests that if
we did measure oxygen 17,

00:35:47.730 --> 00:35:50.300
it might not have
plotted on this line.

00:35:50.300 --> 00:35:53.790
And that would be an absolute
first for any terrestrial rock.

00:35:53.790 --> 00:35:56.835
So now I need to go back to
the big machine in Hawaii

00:35:56.835 --> 00:36:01.140
and I need to make
some more measurements.

00:36:01.140 --> 00:36:02.563
OK, I think that's it.

00:36:02.563 --> 00:36:03.982
Yep.

00:36:03.982 --> 00:36:06.820
[APPLAUSE]

