We have one more speaker
and then after his talk

00:36:17.360 --> 00:36:18.900
then we'll have
them come up and you

00:36:18.900 --> 00:36:21.510
can ask questions of
both of the speakers.

00:36:21.510 --> 00:36:25.390
So our final talk
is by Ben Harden

00:36:25.390 --> 00:36:30.060
who is assistant professor
of oceanography at the Sea

00:36:30.060 --> 00:36:31.550
Education Association.

00:36:31.550 --> 00:36:35.530
I was lucky enough to
get a colleague's cruise

00:36:35.530 --> 00:36:39.230
on one of their sailing
vessels a couple years ago.

00:36:39.230 --> 00:36:42.580
And he also works as a
researcher at Woods Hole

00:36:42.580 --> 00:36:44.810
Oceanographic institute.

00:36:44.810 --> 00:36:49.110
His work centers on ocean
currents in the North Atlantic.

00:36:49.110 --> 00:36:53.900
And this, again, just by
anecdote is of interest to me

00:36:53.900 --> 00:36:58.600
because I teach a course
on navigation and one

00:36:58.600 --> 00:37:00.230
of the things that
has fascinated

00:37:00.230 --> 00:37:05.120
me is the period when the Norse
settled first Iceland and then

00:37:05.120 --> 00:37:06.020
Greenland.

00:37:06.020 --> 00:37:10.930
And there is some evidence
that temperatures in the North

00:37:10.930 --> 00:37:14.810
Atlantic were warmer, and
there is this critical area

00:37:14.810 --> 00:37:19.230
called the Denmark Strait
between Iceland and Greenland

00:37:19.230 --> 00:37:20.400
that had to be crossed.

00:37:20.400 --> 00:37:25.190
And we know that the
colonies in Greenland

00:37:25.190 --> 00:37:27.680
emerged roughly 1000 a.d.

00:37:27.680 --> 00:37:31.330
And then got shut
down around 1350,

00:37:31.330 --> 00:37:33.830
around the time of
the Little Ice Age.

00:37:33.830 --> 00:37:36.470
So this area of
the Denmark Strait

00:37:36.470 --> 00:37:38.780
has been fascinating to
me because it's somehow

00:37:38.780 --> 00:37:42.470
the source of the world's
largest underwater waterfall,

00:37:42.470 --> 00:37:45.180
and has all these strange
currents going on,

00:37:45.180 --> 00:37:48.110
and so I have to
hear about this.

00:37:48.110 --> 00:37:51.720
So his talk is entitled The
Fate of the Gulf Stream.

00:37:51.720 --> 00:37:53.420
So, here's Ben.

