00:38:02.357 --> 00:38:03.940
Thank you to Lydia
first and foremost.

00:38:03.940 --> 00:38:05.900
That was an absolutely
fascinating talk.

00:38:05.900 --> 00:38:08.877
And some stuff that I've never
really ever thought about.

00:38:08.877 --> 00:38:09.460
This is great.

00:38:09.460 --> 00:38:12.043
I think about what happens when
the water, with the water that

00:38:12.043 --> 00:38:13.927
we actually have on
our planet right now.

00:38:13.927 --> 00:38:15.343
So what I'm going
to do today, I'm

00:38:15.343 --> 00:38:18.524
going to talk a little bit about
where the water circulates to

00:38:18.524 --> 00:38:19.440
in the North Atlantic.

00:38:19.440 --> 00:38:21.020
What are some of the
important processes,

00:38:21.020 --> 00:38:22.895
and what are some of
the things that we still

00:38:22.895 --> 00:38:25.550
don't know that we need to know
in order to understand how this

00:38:25.550 --> 00:38:28.120
might change in the future.

00:38:28.120 --> 00:38:30.372
So I like to start
with this image,

00:38:30.372 --> 00:38:31.580
just because I like old maps.

00:38:31.580 --> 00:38:34.500
This is actually from
1943, it's an army map

00:38:34.500 --> 00:38:35.450
of the North Atlantic.

00:38:35.450 --> 00:38:38.830
And it shows the
surface circulation

00:38:38.830 --> 00:38:40.920
that we find in
the North Atlantic.

00:38:40.920 --> 00:38:43.334
I like it because these
lines here are streamlined,

00:38:43.334 --> 00:38:45.750
and it basically picks out
some of the really key features

00:38:45.750 --> 00:38:47.870
of the circulation around
the North Atlantic.

00:38:47.870 --> 00:38:51.414
We have a subtropical
gyre down here

00:38:51.414 --> 00:38:53.580
in the Southern portion of
the North Atlantic, which

00:38:53.580 --> 00:38:55.700
basically takes water
and circulates it

00:38:55.700 --> 00:38:57.200
all the way around.

00:38:57.200 --> 00:39:00.669
And then if we go further north
we have a subpolar gyre up

00:39:00.669 --> 00:39:02.585
in the Irminger Sea, and
that just takes water

00:39:02.585 --> 00:39:04.043
and actually sends
it the other way

00:39:04.043 --> 00:39:09.420
around over the southern
coast of Greenland up there.

00:39:09.420 --> 00:39:11.227
Right over here on
the Western boundary

00:39:11.227 --> 00:39:13.060
is a current you are
probably familiar with.

00:39:13.060 --> 00:39:14.960
That's the Gulf Stream.

00:39:14.960 --> 00:39:18.400
This is a jet of water
that starts off down here

00:39:18.400 --> 00:39:22.460
in the Caribbean region and goes
up the East Coast of the United

00:39:22.460 --> 00:39:23.270
States.

00:39:23.270 --> 00:39:26.070
If this thing was
a fire hose, it

00:39:26.070 --> 00:39:30.860
would be able to fill 10
sports stadia every second.

00:39:30.860 --> 00:39:32.660
So it's pumping a
huge amount of water.

00:39:32.660 --> 00:39:35.140
And the important thing for
climate is that water's warm.

00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:37.720
So as it comes up, it's
actually moving a lot of heat

00:39:37.720 --> 00:39:38.880
away from the equator.

00:39:38.880 --> 00:39:41.250
The equator gets an excess
of heat from the sun.

00:39:41.250 --> 00:39:44.010
The poles get not enough heat.

00:39:44.010 --> 00:39:46.620
So the Gulf Stream is really
instrumental in taking

00:39:46.620 --> 00:39:49.200
some of that heat and pumping
it northwards in the North

00:39:49.200 --> 00:39:49.760
Atlantic.

00:39:49.760 --> 00:39:53.474
And the Gulf Stream
sets off on its journey

00:39:53.474 --> 00:39:54.890
and it actually
ends up coming out

00:39:54.890 --> 00:39:56.930
between these two gyres here.

00:39:56.930 --> 00:39:59.030
Some of it gets deflected
around both ways,

00:39:59.030 --> 00:40:01.170
but you actually
get about 30% of it

00:40:01.170 --> 00:40:03.580
ends up exiting the whole
system and heading up

00:40:03.580 --> 00:40:08.080
into the Nordic seas north
of Great Britain there.

00:40:08.080 --> 00:40:13.289
I want to pause
briefly and point

00:40:13.289 --> 00:40:15.580
out something about physical
oceanographers, of which I

00:40:15.580 --> 00:40:16.500
am a member.

00:40:20.070 --> 00:40:22.198
And that is we love to
draw arrows on maps.

00:40:24.689 --> 00:40:26.230
This is a simulation
where I actually

00:40:26.230 --> 00:40:28.940
take some Earth
data from satellites

00:40:28.940 --> 00:40:30.815
and plot it up in a real
time image of what's

00:40:30.815 --> 00:40:32.856
happening with the currents
in the North Atlantic

00:40:32.856 --> 00:40:33.770
at the moment.

00:40:33.770 --> 00:40:35.410
And so, as I was
drawing on my map

00:40:35.410 --> 00:40:38.440
we had a nice, strong arrow
that was going out here

00:40:38.440 --> 00:40:40.303
across towards Northern Europe.

00:40:40.303 --> 00:40:42.260
But in reality
what's happening is

00:40:42.260 --> 00:40:44.010
we have a meandering
system that's

00:40:44.010 --> 00:40:46.200
chucking up little eddies,
and is being kind of

00:40:46.200 --> 00:40:48.810
chaotic in its progress.

00:40:48.810 --> 00:40:51.860
And if you take it further North
there's a lot of meandering,

00:40:51.860 --> 00:40:54.190
there's a lot of
chaotic movement

00:40:54.190 --> 00:40:56.860
that's going on in this region.

00:40:56.860 --> 00:40:59.067
We do have a drift
of warm water that

00:40:59.067 --> 00:41:00.775
comes up from the gulf
stream and ends up

00:41:00.775 --> 00:41:02.010
up here in the Nordic seas.

00:41:02.010 --> 00:41:03.718
And the question we're
going to ask today

00:41:03.718 --> 00:41:06.190
is what happens to that water
once it crosses that boundary

00:41:06.190 --> 00:41:08.810
up into the Arctic Ocean.

00:41:08.810 --> 00:41:10.570
So, this is the region
that we're going

00:41:10.570 --> 00:41:12.026
to be talking about today.

00:41:12.026 --> 00:41:13.900
The region that John
was talking about that's

00:41:13.900 --> 00:41:16.230
between Greenland and Iceland
here, the Denmark Strait,

00:41:16.230 --> 00:41:17.380
this is actually
the area that I'm

00:41:17.380 --> 00:41:19.296
going to focus primarily
on today because it's

00:41:19.296 --> 00:41:21.780
a really vital region for
the circulation of the North

00:41:21.780 --> 00:41:23.790
Atlantic.

00:41:23.790 --> 00:41:28.040
What we have is this remaining
30% of the Gulf Stream

00:41:28.040 --> 00:41:33.030
comes up into the Nordic seas
as a warm surface current.

00:41:33.030 --> 00:41:34.836
And it flows up,
a majority of it,

00:41:34.836 --> 00:41:36.085
to the north of Scotland here.

00:41:36.085 --> 00:41:38.450
A small sliver of it comes
in around the North coast

00:41:38.450 --> 00:41:40.200
of Iceland.

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:42.260
And the great thing about
physical oceanography

00:41:42.260 --> 00:41:46.590
is that we can follow
these currents by tagging

00:41:46.590 --> 00:41:48.250
their unique fingerprints.

00:41:48.250 --> 00:41:50.720
So each current
has a temperature

00:41:50.720 --> 00:41:53.240
and it has a
salinity, a saltiness.

00:41:53.240 --> 00:41:54.970
And by looking at
those two properties,

00:41:54.970 --> 00:41:56.770
we can actually create a
fingerprint for that current.

00:41:56.770 --> 00:41:58.360
And then as we
follow it along, we

00:41:58.360 --> 00:42:01.360
can actually work
out where it goes.

00:42:01.360 --> 00:42:03.010
The important thing
about this current

00:42:03.010 --> 00:42:05.260
is that it's very, very
warm as it comes in.

00:42:05.260 --> 00:42:07.325
That's the reason why we
have tropical conditions

00:42:07.325 --> 00:42:10.040
at the south coast of
Cornwall in the UK.

00:42:10.040 --> 00:42:13.680
It's the reason why the most
northerly botanic gardens

00:42:13.680 --> 00:42:15.470
in the world is in
Tromso in Norway.

00:42:15.470 --> 00:42:17.810
This current is bringing
a lot of heat northwards.

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:20.400
It's vital to the
climates of these regions.

00:42:20.400 --> 00:42:23.360
If we didn't have this warm
flow of water coming northwards,

00:42:23.360 --> 00:42:26.410
we'd be in a very similar
climatic situation to Labrador

00:42:26.410 --> 00:42:28.430
or Alaska in our climate.

00:42:28.430 --> 00:42:32.050
So, you know, these are really,
really important inputs of heat

00:42:32.050 --> 00:42:34.600
into this region.

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:37.830
So we have this warm water
flowing into this region.

00:42:37.830 --> 00:42:39.890
This region here is
called the Nordic seas.

00:42:39.890 --> 00:42:42.220
It's basically the gateway
into the Arctic Ocean,

00:42:42.220 --> 00:42:44.580
which is up here.

00:42:44.580 --> 00:42:47.770
The Arctic Ocean, though,
is an enclosed basin.

00:42:47.770 --> 00:42:49.824
There's no real way
out once you go in.

00:42:49.824 --> 00:42:51.490
There's a couple of
little gaps, there's

00:42:51.490 --> 00:42:53.700
one over here,
the Bering Strait,

00:42:53.700 --> 00:42:56.060
and there's some areas through
the archipelago in Canada

00:42:56.060 --> 00:42:59.120
that water can eke through,
but not in great quantity.

00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:01.260
So, the situation
our warm water's got

00:43:01.260 --> 00:43:03.470
is once it comes
in, it can't keep

00:43:03.470 --> 00:43:05.546
coming in unless some
water is flowing out.

00:43:05.546 --> 00:43:07.670
Otherwise, we're just going
to keep piling, piling,

00:43:07.670 --> 00:43:09.480
piling all this water
up in the North,

00:43:09.480 --> 00:43:11.580
and it won't be able to do that.

00:43:11.580 --> 00:43:14.500
One of the primary ways that we
exchange that warm water that

00:43:14.500 --> 00:43:18.820
goes north is with dense water
that's coming back south.

00:43:18.820 --> 00:43:21.810
And this what is coming back
south not at the surface,

00:43:21.810 --> 00:43:23.860
but deep in the ocean.

00:43:23.860 --> 00:43:26.380
It's actually passing
across, conveniently for us

00:43:26.380 --> 00:43:28.020
who you want to
measure it, there's

00:43:28.020 --> 00:43:31.040
a ridge, an oceanic ridge
that runs between Greenland,

00:43:31.040 --> 00:43:32.880
Iceland, the
Faroes, and Scotland

00:43:32.880 --> 00:43:34.240
that has some small gaps in it.

00:43:34.240 --> 00:43:37.310
This ridge is about six to
1,000 meters deep in the ocean.

00:43:37.310 --> 00:43:38.950
It has these small gaps.

00:43:38.950 --> 00:43:41.550
One is the Denmark Strait,
there's the Faroe bank channel

00:43:41.550 --> 00:43:43.925
over here, and there's a small
one to the east of Iceland

00:43:43.925 --> 00:43:44.589
as well.

00:43:44.589 --> 00:43:45.964
The Denmark Strait
is the one I'm

00:43:45.964 --> 00:43:48.338
going to focus on today because
it's the primary channel.

00:43:48.338 --> 00:43:49.830
It is the largest
of the overflows.

00:43:49.830 --> 00:43:51.746
It's ultimately the
densest of the overthrows.

00:43:51.746 --> 00:43:53.730
It has the largest
contributor to the, kind of,

00:43:53.730 --> 00:43:56.334
return flow of water.

00:43:56.334 --> 00:43:57.750
And the basic
question that people

00:43:57.750 --> 00:43:59.250
have been asking
for quite some time

00:43:59.250 --> 00:44:03.090
is how do we take this warm
water that is flowing in

00:44:03.090 --> 00:44:04.970
and turn it into that
dense water that's

00:44:04.970 --> 00:44:07.600
going to flow back out again?

00:44:07.600 --> 00:44:10.550
Basically, as a side
schematic, it looks like this.

00:44:10.550 --> 00:44:12.410
We have warm water flowing in.

00:44:12.410 --> 00:44:15.020
We need to somehow
convert this warm water

00:44:15.020 --> 00:44:18.300
into dense water that can then
go over this ridge and cascade

00:44:18.300 --> 00:44:19.390
down to the deep ocean.

00:44:19.390 --> 00:44:22.850
This is, as John was
saying, one of the largest

00:44:22.850 --> 00:44:24.460
underwater waterfalls
in the world.

00:44:24.460 --> 00:44:27.130
It's cascading from
about 600 meters depth

00:44:27.130 --> 00:44:29.250
all the way down to
2 and 1/2 kilometers

00:44:29.250 --> 00:44:31.770
or further as it
goes back southwards.

00:44:31.770 --> 00:44:34.590
Hugely dynamic system.

00:44:34.590 --> 00:44:37.110
But it all starts
in how we produce

00:44:37.110 --> 00:44:39.260
the dense water, the
deep, dense water

00:44:39.260 --> 00:44:42.250
north of the Denmark Strait.

00:44:42.250 --> 00:44:44.620
So oceanographers,
physical oceanographers,

00:44:44.620 --> 00:44:47.100
have mulled this over
for many decades.

00:44:47.100 --> 00:44:49.260
Back in the 80s,
everyone was basically

00:44:49.260 --> 00:44:51.520
centered on the idea of OK,
you just send warm water

00:44:51.520 --> 00:44:52.650
into that basin.

00:44:52.650 --> 00:44:54.440
You hit it with
intense cold winds.

00:44:54.440 --> 00:44:56.920
Maybe you form some sea
ice which rejects some salt

00:44:56.920 --> 00:44:57.610
into the water.

00:44:57.610 --> 00:44:59.735
And eventually that water
just becomes dense enough

00:44:59.735 --> 00:45:03.820
in the central basins that it
just sinks and flows back out.

00:45:03.820 --> 00:45:08.020
This was challenged in the
1990s by a researcher called

00:45:08.020 --> 00:45:10.780
[INAUDIBLE] who proposed
that instead of looking

00:45:10.780 --> 00:45:13.350
in the middle of the ocean
here, we should actually

00:45:13.350 --> 00:45:17.150
follow the Gulf Stream on its
path and see where it goes.

00:45:17.150 --> 00:45:19.760
And she proposed that
actually what's happening

00:45:19.760 --> 00:45:22.070
is this Gulf Stream
water, as it comes in,

00:45:22.070 --> 00:45:24.340
is just flowing progressively
around the outside

00:45:24.340 --> 00:45:25.150
of the Nordic sea.

00:45:25.150 --> 00:45:27.570
It's being hit by winds.

00:45:27.570 --> 00:45:29.640
Sea ice is being
formed around it.

00:45:29.640 --> 00:45:32.670
And basically you just get
colder and saltier all the way

00:45:32.670 --> 00:45:34.610
around until
eventually it can sink

00:45:34.610 --> 00:45:36.876
along the edge of
the continent here

00:45:36.876 --> 00:45:38.000
and flow straight back out.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:39.458
So we've got like
a pipeline system

00:45:39.458 --> 00:45:44.142
now, rather than a
more diffuse system.

00:45:44.142 --> 00:45:47.560
If we zoom in to the Denmark
Strait in particular,

00:45:47.560 --> 00:45:51.490
this current we call the
East Greenland Current

00:45:51.490 --> 00:45:53.490
because it flows on the
east coast of Greenland.

00:45:53.490 --> 00:45:55.620
It comes in here,
passes over here,

00:45:55.620 --> 00:45:57.330
this is our sill at
600 meters, and then

00:45:57.330 --> 00:46:00.509
it's about to cascade down
into the really deep ocean.

00:46:00.509 --> 00:46:02.300
And what you can do is
you can go out there

00:46:02.300 --> 00:46:03.966
and you can take a
ship across this line

00:46:03.966 --> 00:46:06.750
and lower some instrumentation
and look at the fingerprints

00:46:06.750 --> 00:46:07.650
of those currents.

00:46:07.650 --> 00:46:12.840
And you can really see those
significant fingerprints.

00:46:12.840 --> 00:46:14.960
This is a cross-section
of the ocean.

00:46:14.960 --> 00:46:17.390
Over here is the
Greenland coast.

00:46:17.390 --> 00:46:18.180
This is the shelf.

00:46:18.180 --> 00:46:20.638
And this is dropping off into
the middle the Denmark Strait

00:46:20.638 --> 00:46:21.870
here.

00:46:21.870 --> 00:46:23.980
Everything below
this white line here

00:46:23.980 --> 00:46:25.927
is destined to
join the overflow.

00:46:25.927 --> 00:46:28.010
And what you can see is
we have temperature on top

00:46:28.010 --> 00:46:30.040
here, and salinity
on the bottom here,

00:46:30.040 --> 00:46:32.690
is that below that white
line we have this nice blob

00:46:32.690 --> 00:46:34.875
of warm, salty water.

00:46:34.875 --> 00:46:37.125
It's got a lot denser since
it was in the Gulf Stream,

00:46:37.125 --> 00:46:40.260
but really that fingerprint
is still on that current.

00:46:40.260 --> 00:46:43.580
We know that it came from
the Gulf Stream water.

00:46:43.580 --> 00:46:45.360
And more importantly,
it's flowing out

00:46:45.360 --> 00:46:48.870
of the page towards
us, towards the Strait.

00:46:48.870 --> 00:46:50.960
Of also note, up
here on the shelf

00:46:50.960 --> 00:46:54.330
we have a lot of very, very
cold, very, very fresh water.

00:46:54.330 --> 00:46:56.285
And that's the outflow
from the Arctic Ocean.

00:46:56.285 --> 00:46:57.910
So the Arctic dumps
a lot of freshwater

00:46:57.910 --> 00:46:59.897
into the ocean, which
then flows out as well.

00:46:59.897 --> 00:47:02.230
So actually, it's a combined
current. the East Greenland

00:47:02.230 --> 00:47:02.880
Current.

00:47:02.880 --> 00:47:06.610
We have a deep, dense component
that came from the Gulf Stream

00:47:06.610 --> 00:47:10.580
originally, and then we have
this fresh surface outflow

00:47:10.580 --> 00:47:13.407
which is joining
it at the surface.

00:47:13.407 --> 00:47:15.490
So everything was great,
everything was hunky dory

00:47:15.490 --> 00:47:16.272
back in the 1990s.

00:47:16.272 --> 00:47:17.980
We knew where this
water was coming from.

00:47:17.980 --> 00:47:20.000
We knew how the Denmark
Strait got it's water.

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:22.720
We knew where the key regions
were to focus on in order

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:25.420
to understand how
the water might

00:47:25.420 --> 00:47:28.010
be changed under future
climate change [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:28.010 --> 00:47:28.940
Bingo.

00:47:28.940 --> 00:47:32.396
2000s came, some
pesky Icelanders

00:47:32.396 --> 00:47:34.520
discovered a brand new
current that no one had ever

00:47:34.520 --> 00:47:38.650
seen before flowing on the
North coast of Iceland.

00:47:38.650 --> 00:47:41.190
This is not an
uncommon occurrence

00:47:41.190 --> 00:47:43.500
to discover currents
in this region.

00:47:43.500 --> 00:47:45.410
They're very, very
small in scale

00:47:45.410 --> 00:47:48.190
compared to the Gulf Stream
because of rotational effects

00:47:48.190 --> 00:47:50.544
as you get higher up
towards the poles.

00:47:50.544 --> 00:47:51.960
But this is a brand
new discovery,

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:54.376
and this was also bringing
dense water towards the Strait,

00:47:54.376 --> 00:47:57.160
but it wasn't coming from the
same direction as the East

00:47:57.160 --> 00:47:57.410
Greenland Current.

00:47:57.410 --> 00:47:59.660
It was coming from around
the corner, around the coast

00:47:59.660 --> 00:48:00.690
of Iceland over here.

00:48:00.690 --> 00:48:02.315
They called it the
North Icelandic Jet,

00:48:02.315 --> 00:48:04.110
and if you expand
that cross-section

00:48:04.110 --> 00:48:07.030
that I showed originally,
all the way out over here,

00:48:07.030 --> 00:48:09.820
this is Iceland now over
here, you can see roughly

00:48:09.820 --> 00:48:11.450
where this dashed
line is here we

00:48:11.450 --> 00:48:15.866
got a demarcation from this
warm, salty overflow water that

00:48:15.866 --> 00:48:17.740
was going to be in the
East Greenland Current

00:48:17.740 --> 00:48:23.140
and you suddenly jump to a much
fresher, much colder product.

00:48:23.140 --> 00:48:25.560
A fingerprint that was
distinctly different

00:48:25.560 --> 00:48:27.260
from the Gulf
Stream, and we needed

00:48:27.260 --> 00:48:28.890
to know where that
was coming from.

00:48:28.890 --> 00:48:32.560
Importantly, again, it's coming
out of the page towards us.

00:48:32.560 --> 00:48:35.806
It's flowing this
way towards the cell.

00:48:35.806 --> 00:48:38.840
Of note, also, up here we've
got some very warm, salty water.

00:48:38.840 --> 00:48:41.800
That's that little eking
stream of warm water

00:48:41.800 --> 00:48:45.147
we had flowing in round
the top of Iceland.

00:48:45.147 --> 00:48:46.980
So we've got that warm
water coming directly

00:48:46.980 --> 00:48:50.640
in from the Gulf Stream
as well in that region.

00:48:50.640 --> 00:48:53.760
So that's basically the
situation as we understood it.

00:48:53.760 --> 00:48:55.835
We had a very well
known source of water,

00:48:55.835 --> 00:48:58.390
and all of a sudden we had
this mysterious current that

00:48:58.390 --> 00:49:00.265
was coming from a new
direction and we didn't

00:49:00.265 --> 00:49:02.312
know where it's coming from.

00:49:02.312 --> 00:49:04.270
And so that's significant,
looking at those two

00:49:04.270 --> 00:49:06.770
dense pathways, because if we
don't know where that water is

00:49:06.770 --> 00:49:09.104
coming from, we don't know
what formation regions are

00:49:09.104 --> 00:49:10.020
going to be important.

00:49:10.020 --> 00:49:11.394
If we change the
wind conditions,

00:49:11.394 --> 00:49:13.980
if we change freshwater
inputs, if we change sea ice

00:49:13.980 --> 00:49:16.100
distributions, how
would that affect

00:49:16.100 --> 00:49:18.265
the water that's being
produced that then feeds in?

00:49:18.265 --> 00:49:20.140
How would that then
affect how much water can

00:49:20.140 --> 00:49:21.520
flow north in the Gulf Stream?

00:49:24.150 --> 00:49:27.900
The reason we've only recently
discovered these pathways

00:49:27.900 --> 00:49:29.570
and been asking
these questions is

00:49:29.570 --> 00:49:32.360
that this is a pretty
perilous place to visit.

00:49:32.360 --> 00:49:34.540
As a context to the
video I'm about the show,

00:49:34.540 --> 00:49:37.090
I did my undergraduate
in physics

00:49:37.090 --> 00:49:38.510
and my master's in physics.

00:49:38.510 --> 00:49:41.850
I dabbled in particle physics
and astrophysics for a while

00:49:41.850 --> 00:49:44.530
before deciding that I
wanted to do something

00:49:44.530 --> 00:49:46.700
more environmental in my focus.

00:49:46.700 --> 00:49:49.110
And so I signed up
for a PhD Program

00:49:49.110 --> 00:49:52.560
at the University of East Anglia
where my supervisor promptly

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:53.700
sent me to sea.

00:49:53.700 --> 00:49:57.060
And said go to sea,
there's a research vessel

00:49:57.060 --> 00:50:00.260
that's going to be out
in the Denmark Strait,

00:50:00.260 --> 00:50:03.980
you're going to study
the wind conditions

00:50:03.980 --> 00:50:06.306
around the coast of
Greenland and your thesis

00:50:06.306 --> 00:50:08.180
is all going to be about
extreme wind events.

00:50:08.180 --> 00:50:08.910
I was like, this is fine.

00:50:08.910 --> 00:50:09.570
I can do this.

00:50:09.570 --> 00:50:13.590
He said, go stand out on
the back of the vessel

00:50:13.590 --> 00:50:18.741
and launch meter wide helium
balloons into the storm.

00:50:18.741 --> 00:50:20.366
I've got this on mute
because you don't

00:50:20.366 --> 00:50:23.490
want to hear the commentary.

00:50:23.490 --> 00:50:24.810
-How big is that wave?

00:50:24.810 --> 00:50:27.740
-Oh, it's, it was at least
as high as the bridge,

00:50:27.740 --> 00:50:28.809
if not more.

00:50:28.809 --> 00:50:30.600
This is the research
vessel in [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:30.600 --> 00:50:33.760
And so my job during
this first installment

00:50:33.760 --> 00:50:36.592
of my oceanography career was
to go out and try and stand

00:50:36.592 --> 00:50:38.800
on the back of that ship to
launch a weather balloon.

00:50:38.800 --> 00:50:40.200
-Were you tied in?

00:50:40.200 --> 00:50:41.554
-Just about, yeah.

00:50:44.664 --> 00:50:46.080
It was an exhilarating
experience,

00:50:46.080 --> 00:50:48.540
but the interesting--
within the context

00:50:48.540 --> 00:50:52.330
of this interdisciplinary
notion that John

00:50:52.330 --> 00:50:54.790
was talking about in
the introduction, one

00:50:54.790 --> 00:50:57.740
of the great things
about this region

00:50:57.740 --> 00:51:00.460
is there's so much influence
of the atmosphere on the ocean.

00:51:00.460 --> 00:51:01.980
This is how I got
interested in oceanography

00:51:01.980 --> 00:51:04.188
in the first place was seeing
these winds and saying,

00:51:04.188 --> 00:51:06.390
wow, you know, this is
a dynamic environment.

00:51:06.390 --> 00:51:09.930
I wonder what these winds
are doing to the ocean.

00:51:09.930 --> 00:51:12.169
So it's very hard to
go to this region.

00:51:12.169 --> 00:51:14.210
You go out there in these
ships, you try and take

00:51:14.210 --> 00:51:15.876
these measurements,
and we only actually

00:51:15.876 --> 00:51:18.670
have four snapshots
across this current system

00:51:18.670 --> 00:51:23.711
in eight years of asking.

00:51:23.711 --> 00:51:25.960
So you've really only got
this little tiny look at it.

00:51:25.960 --> 00:51:29.040
And the problem with it
is that every time you

00:51:29.040 --> 00:51:31.920
go out with the ship the
current system looks different.

00:51:31.920 --> 00:51:33.790
You want to measure how much
water is coming from each place

00:51:33.790 --> 00:51:35.831
if you want to know how
much each is contributing

00:51:35.831 --> 00:51:36.530
to the overflow.

00:51:36.530 --> 00:51:40.562
2004 the East Greenland
Current, 85% of the overflow.

00:51:40.562 --> 00:51:42.020
Great, cool, we've
got this sorted.

00:51:42.020 --> 00:51:44.490
We don't need to worry about
the North Icelandic Jet.

00:51:44.490 --> 00:51:46.630
2012, oh heck, it's
gone the other way.

00:51:46.630 --> 00:51:50.650
60% of it's in the
North Icelandic Jet.

00:51:50.650 --> 00:51:52.040
So we've got a problem here.

00:51:52.040 --> 00:51:55.616
We don't know whether this
is-- is this a seasonal thing?

00:51:55.616 --> 00:51:57.490
Because we actually only
go out in the summer

00:51:57.490 --> 00:51:58.640
to measure these things.

00:51:58.640 --> 00:52:00.530
What's even happening
in the winter time?

00:52:00.530 --> 00:52:03.580
Is this, if we went out a week
later would it be different?

00:52:03.580 --> 00:52:05.420
If we went out a year later?

00:52:05.420 --> 00:52:07.356
You know, is this
a decadal trend?

00:52:07.356 --> 00:52:09.480
Or is this something that's
happening very quickly?

00:52:09.480 --> 00:52:12.200
And we really don't have a
way of doing that if we just

00:52:12.200 --> 00:52:13.810
keep going out with
ships one by one

00:52:13.810 --> 00:52:16.330
to try and measure
these systems.

00:52:16.330 --> 00:52:19.160
So the way that we
solved the problem

00:52:19.160 --> 00:52:22.810
is kind of a technological
solution, which

00:52:22.810 --> 00:52:25.360
is to go out with a
series of moorings

00:52:25.360 --> 00:52:27.520
across the whole current system.

00:52:27.520 --> 00:52:29.270
So a mooring, an
oceanographic mooring,

00:52:29.270 --> 00:52:30.970
is basically a big
anchor that sits

00:52:30.970 --> 00:52:33.880
on the sea floor with
a wire that comes up

00:52:33.880 --> 00:52:35.400
to a very buoyant float.

00:52:35.400 --> 00:52:37.930
We keep our floats about
100 meters below the surface

00:52:37.930 --> 00:52:39.930
because there's a lot of
icebergs in the region,

00:52:39.930 --> 00:52:41.471
there's a lot of
fishing vessels that

00:52:41.471 --> 00:52:42.870
will come along and smash them.

00:52:42.870 --> 00:52:46.930
We lose a lot of moorings
in this region because

00:52:46.930 --> 00:52:48.904
of those kind of activities.

00:52:48.904 --> 00:52:50.320
So we have to be
a little careful,

00:52:50.320 --> 00:52:52.292
and the old
oceanography adage is

00:52:52.292 --> 00:52:53.875
you don't put something
into the water

00:52:53.875 --> 00:52:55.880
that you're expecting
to get back.

00:52:55.880 --> 00:52:59.116
You have to be a little bit
realistic about this process.

00:52:59.116 --> 00:53:00.740
And I thought I'd
just say a little bit

00:53:00.740 --> 00:53:01.870
about how we deploy
them, because I

00:53:01.870 --> 00:53:03.161
think it's kind of fascinating.

00:53:03.161 --> 00:53:04.860
You have to take the
ship back out there

00:53:04.860 --> 00:53:06.039
to put these things in.

00:53:06.039 --> 00:53:08.580
And the way that you put them
in is you kind of go backwards.

00:53:08.580 --> 00:53:09.913
This is, again, the [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:09.913 --> 00:53:12.090
This is a much nicer day
in the Denmark Strait.

00:53:12.090 --> 00:53:14.214
We got very lucky on
this particular cruise.

00:53:14.214 --> 00:53:16.130
And the idea is you're
on the back of the ship

00:53:16.130 --> 00:53:18.030
and you put it in backwards.

00:53:18.030 --> 00:53:20.639
You put the float in
first, the top float.

00:53:20.639 --> 00:53:22.055
Put that in the
water, release it,

00:53:22.055 --> 00:53:24.000
and you've got the wire now
attached to the bottom of it,

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:24.570
right.

00:53:24.570 --> 00:53:26.430
And you now steam
away from that and you

00:53:26.430 --> 00:53:28.290
start laying out
your wire, you start

00:53:28.290 --> 00:53:30.850
adding the instrumentation
one by one,

00:53:30.850 --> 00:53:32.270
and you just keep
spooling it out.

00:53:32.270 --> 00:53:36.530
And eventually you end up with
the anchor that goes over last.

00:53:36.530 --> 00:53:39.215
So you lower the anchor in,
it's just a big chunk of steel.

00:53:39.215 --> 00:53:41.590
Then when you get to exactly
the right point in the ocean

00:53:41.590 --> 00:53:46.140
where you want to drop it
you trigger the release,

00:53:46.140 --> 00:53:50.050
the anchor drops,
buoys go down, and then

00:53:50.050 --> 00:53:51.960
that top float comes
water skiing towards you

00:53:51.960 --> 00:53:55.600
as it's being dragged
down underneath the water.

00:53:58.240 --> 00:54:00.400
And so then you
leave them there.

00:54:00.400 --> 00:54:03.290
We actually left 12 of
them across the whole thing

00:54:03.290 --> 00:54:04.827
between Iceland and Greenland.

00:54:04.827 --> 00:54:06.910
You leave them there for
a year, you go back home,

00:54:06.910 --> 00:54:08.530
you go back to
your regular life,

00:54:08.530 --> 00:54:10.280
and you try not to think
about it because there's

00:54:10.280 --> 00:54:11.404
no point worrying about it.

00:54:11.404 --> 00:54:13.130
You might go out next
year and discover

00:54:13.130 --> 00:54:15.240
that every single one of
them has been destroyed,

00:54:15.240 --> 00:54:16.560
or taken away somewhere else.

00:54:16.560 --> 00:54:22.030
You have to do the best you can
to put that out of your mind.

00:54:22.030 --> 00:54:24.320
And then you do go
out a year later

00:54:24.320 --> 00:54:26.860
to find out whether these
things are still there,

00:54:26.860 --> 00:54:29.500
and one of the things about
going to pick these moorings up

00:54:29.500 --> 00:54:32.860
is that they're
below the surface

00:54:32.860 --> 00:54:34.870
and you can't see
them from the boat.

00:54:34.870 --> 00:54:36.909
So you have to find
them electronically,

00:54:36.909 --> 00:54:39.450
and you have to, using a fish
finder, or something like that,

00:54:39.450 --> 00:54:41.440
go back to the place
where you left them.

00:54:41.440 --> 00:54:45.180
And because radio waves travel
really badly through the water,

00:54:45.180 --> 00:54:47.000
you can't just send
a radio signal out

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:48.230
to say, hey, release it.

00:54:48.230 --> 00:54:51.180
You actually have to use sound,
sound waves, in the water.

00:54:51.180 --> 00:54:53.910
And so what you do is
you go back out again

00:54:53.910 --> 00:54:57.200
on a different ship, also a nice
day off the coast of Greenland.

00:54:57.200 --> 00:55:01.250
And this is a little
speaker, basically,

00:55:01.250 --> 00:55:03.850
that sends out sound
waves into the water

00:55:03.850 --> 00:55:05.980
over the side of the ship.

00:55:05.980 --> 00:55:08.860
And we send a coded
series of pings which

00:55:08.860 --> 00:55:10.240
the anchor is listening for.

00:55:10.240 --> 00:55:12.861
And if we send the right
combination at the right code,

00:55:12.861 --> 00:55:14.360
basically, to the
anchor, it's going

00:55:14.360 --> 00:55:16.080
to release its
grip on the anchor

00:55:16.080 --> 00:55:18.930
and then the whole thing's going
to float up to the surface.

00:55:18.930 --> 00:55:20.390
But you don't know where
it's going to come up.

00:55:20.390 --> 00:55:21.624
And everyone looks
at the ocean, and you

00:55:21.624 --> 00:55:23.707
don't know whether it's
actually going to show up.

00:55:23.707 --> 00:55:26.185
And all of a sudden it pings
up onto the surface there.

00:55:26.185 --> 00:55:28.930
Now it's floating around and
you have to go pick it up

00:55:28.930 --> 00:55:30.930
with your ship.

00:55:30.930 --> 00:55:33.570
Those are the good
days when that happens.

00:55:33.570 --> 00:55:36.530
The bad days can be when you
send a ping out it says, OK,

00:55:36.530 --> 00:55:39.700
I've released, and then nothing
shows up at the surface.

00:55:39.700 --> 00:55:42.520
And then you have to go
out with-- you actually

00:55:42.520 --> 00:55:44.770
put a long grappling
hook out behind the ship

00:55:44.770 --> 00:55:47.260
and just go around, and
round, and round in the ocean

00:55:47.260 --> 00:55:48.843
hoping you're going
to grab something.

00:55:48.843 --> 00:55:51.333
And then you drive away, hoping
it's going to kind of drag

00:55:51.333 --> 00:55:55.350
the whole thing with it.

00:55:55.350 --> 00:55:57.630
So we actually got really,
really lucky on this trip.

00:55:57.630 --> 00:55:58.790
All 12 of them came back.

00:55:58.790 --> 00:56:00.873
This is not something that
happens very regularly.

00:56:00.873 --> 00:56:03.810
So we've actually been able to
now look at the whole Strait

00:56:03.810 --> 00:56:06.680
wide circulation in
some detail, and not

00:56:06.680 --> 00:56:11.030
just through four snapshots
of what the current's doing.

00:56:11.030 --> 00:56:15.675
We now have 1008 snapshots
over the course of a year.

00:56:15.675 --> 00:56:18.300
And so we can do things that we
haven't been able to do before,

00:56:18.300 --> 00:56:20.930
like produce an average
hydrographic section,

00:56:20.930 --> 00:56:24.377
an average temperature and
salinity across the strait.

00:56:24.377 --> 00:56:25.960
And this looks largely
similar to some

00:56:25.960 --> 00:56:27.230
of the stuff we've seen before.

00:56:27.230 --> 00:56:28.771
Again, Greenland on
the left, Iceland

00:56:28.771 --> 00:56:31.520
on the right, this white line
is that line that's important.

00:56:31.520 --> 00:56:33.978
Everything below that is going
to join the overflow, that's

00:56:33.978 --> 00:56:37.392
the dense water that's
going to go head back South.

00:56:37.392 --> 00:56:40.162
Up on the surface,
on the left here, we

00:56:40.162 --> 00:56:42.040
have that cold
fresh surface water

00:56:42.040 --> 00:56:43.310
from the Arctic pouring out.

00:56:43.310 --> 00:56:44.950
That's all the melt water.

00:56:44.950 --> 00:56:47.670
Over right here that's
the warmer, saltier waters

00:56:47.670 --> 00:56:50.600
coming in from the Atlantic
Ocean surface, those two

00:56:50.600 --> 00:56:51.960
surface currents.

00:56:51.960 --> 00:56:56.270
And then deeper down, below
that density interface,

00:56:56.270 --> 00:57:00.310
we have warm, salty water from
the East Greenland Current,

00:57:00.310 --> 00:57:02.597
and then, again, colder,
fresher water over

00:57:02.597 --> 00:57:04.680
on the Iceland side from
the North Icelandic jets.

00:57:04.680 --> 00:57:07.284
We have, again, seen
these fingerprints now

00:57:07.284 --> 00:57:08.700
over the course
of the whole year.

00:57:08.700 --> 00:57:10.940
So we can start to say, hey,
we think the North Icelandic

00:57:10.940 --> 00:57:12.970
Jet's actually going to be an
important thing all year round,

00:57:12.970 --> 00:57:15.110
it's not necessarily
just a summertime thing.

00:57:15.110 --> 00:57:17.030
We even went further
and were able to compare

00:57:17.030 --> 00:57:22.490
those fingerprints of those
two currents to historic data

00:57:22.490 --> 00:57:24.730
from upstream of
the Denmark Strait.

00:57:24.730 --> 00:57:27.340
So this is our mooring array
here across the strait.

00:57:27.340 --> 00:57:30.145
This is one mooring over here
in the East Greenland Current,

00:57:30.145 --> 00:57:32.020
and one over here in
the North Icelandic Jet.

00:57:32.020 --> 00:57:34.603
And we can actually compare the
fingerprints between these two

00:57:34.603 --> 00:57:36.270
regions, and they
match up really well.

00:57:36.270 --> 00:57:37.490
So we've actually been
able to show not just

00:57:37.490 --> 00:57:38.850
that we have two
different kind of waters,

00:57:38.850 --> 00:57:40.900
but they actually come
from two different places

00:57:40.900 --> 00:57:43.590
along the coast.

00:57:43.590 --> 00:57:45.830
I wanted to show you
earlier about the fact

00:57:45.830 --> 00:57:48.720
that we love drawing
arrows on maps

00:57:48.720 --> 00:57:51.540
to point out where the
currents are going from and to.

00:57:51.540 --> 00:57:58.120
The reality, again, is that
we can't quite be so specific.

00:57:58.120 --> 00:58:01.690
This is a video of the
current velocities,

00:58:01.690 --> 00:58:04.440
the speed of the currents
coming through the red.

00:58:04.440 --> 00:58:06.560
And Greenland on the left,
Iceland on the right.

00:58:06.560 --> 00:58:09.530
Red colors mean the
current's coming towards us,

00:58:09.530 --> 00:58:15.590
and blue colors mean the
current's heading away from us.

00:58:15.590 --> 00:58:18.180
And so at times it
looks kind of stable.

00:58:18.180 --> 00:58:20.490
But then after a while
it starts to cascade.

00:58:20.490 --> 00:58:22.620
And you get blobs of
blue, and blobs of red,

00:58:22.620 --> 00:58:24.570
and they shift from
one side to the other

00:58:24.570 --> 00:58:27.940
when things start coming in
and going out of the region.

00:58:27.940 --> 00:58:29.500
And this is just to
exemplify that we

00:58:29.500 --> 00:58:32.080
love drawing these arrows that
point currents in singular

00:58:32.080 --> 00:58:35.410
directions, but in reality
we have a very dynamic system

00:58:35.410 --> 00:58:37.910
that's eddying and distorting
throughout the year.

00:58:37.910 --> 00:58:42.620
So, how can we use this
kind of information

00:58:42.620 --> 00:58:45.120
to actually say how much water
is coming from each direction

00:58:45.120 --> 00:58:47.160
if it's so dynamic?

00:58:47.160 --> 00:58:49.150
And we use those
fingerprints, in general,

00:58:49.150 --> 00:58:50.590
to be able to do this.

00:58:50.590 --> 00:58:54.190
Say, this is one snapshot
of the current at one time.

00:58:54.190 --> 00:58:56.352
Here's a current
coming out of the page,

00:58:56.352 --> 00:58:58.310
here's another current
over here, a little tiny

00:58:58.310 --> 00:58:59.422
one, that's up here.

00:58:59.422 --> 00:59:01.130
And here is our
temperature and salinity.

00:59:01.130 --> 00:59:03.950
And then, again, you can
see those same fingerprints,

00:59:03.950 --> 00:59:07.290
warm, salty over
here, and then colder

00:59:07.290 --> 00:59:09.530
and fresher over on that side.

00:59:09.530 --> 00:59:13.190
And we can basically draw a line
at every time, every snapshot

00:59:13.190 --> 00:59:16.880
that we have that divides the
currents between currents that

00:59:16.880 --> 00:59:19.945
are carrying the East Greenland
Current water, these two here,

00:59:19.945 --> 00:59:22.320
and currents that are carrying
North Icelandic Jet water,

00:59:22.320 --> 00:59:23.750
this little current up here.

00:59:23.750 --> 00:59:27.170
So we can actually use the
data about the fingerprints

00:59:27.170 --> 00:59:29.770
to divide these currents
up into what kind of water

00:59:29.770 --> 00:59:31.900
they're bringing.

00:59:31.900 --> 00:59:34.760
And so the results of that
are shown in this figure.

00:59:34.760 --> 00:59:37.330
It's a time series that
shows the percentage

00:59:37.330 --> 00:59:39.950
from the Greenland side, the
percentage of East Greenland

00:59:39.950 --> 00:59:41.730
Current that's in our array.

00:59:41.730 --> 00:59:43.306
And so over here
would be entirely

00:59:43.306 --> 00:59:45.680
East Greenland Current, over
here would be entirely North

00:59:45.680 --> 00:59:48.220
Icelandic Jet.

00:59:48.220 --> 00:59:51.990
So the light line is what's
happening every single eight

00:59:51.990 --> 00:59:58.200
hours, the dark line is a
smoothed average over 30 days.

00:59:58.200 --> 01:00:00.370
And so what we can see
is, actually, this current

01:00:00.370 --> 01:00:01.730
is extremely dynamic.

01:00:01.730 --> 01:00:04.300
It's jumping from 100%
East Greenland Current

01:00:04.300 --> 01:00:06.524
to 100% North
Icelandic Jet at times.

01:00:06.524 --> 01:00:07.940
It's going back
and forth, someone

01:00:07.940 --> 01:00:09.410
is turning the
faucet on, and off,

01:00:09.410 --> 01:00:12.770
and on, and off, on different
sides of this Strait

01:00:12.770 --> 01:00:14.551
to bring water through.

01:00:14.551 --> 01:00:16.800
You can also see that there's
some kind of seasonality

01:00:16.800 --> 01:00:20.100
as well, maybe in the wintertime
the East Greenland Current

01:00:20.100 --> 01:00:21.170
brings more water.

01:00:21.170 --> 01:00:24.340
Maybe the North Icelandic
Jet's a bigger player

01:00:24.340 --> 01:00:26.940
in the summertime when we've
seen it before in our, kind of,

01:00:26.940 --> 01:00:29.230
snapshots.

01:00:29.230 --> 01:00:30.960
So there's much to
learn from this.

01:00:30.960 --> 01:00:32.960
The simplest thing we can
do is take an average.

01:00:32.960 --> 01:00:34.770
It's the first time we're
able to do this and actually

01:00:34.770 --> 01:00:37.400
robustly say how much water's
coming from each direction,

01:00:37.400 --> 01:00:39.840
and about 70% of it's coming
from the East Greenland

01:00:39.840 --> 01:00:45.320
Current and 30% is coming
from the North Icelandic Jet.

01:00:45.320 --> 01:00:47.680
So we now have a
pretty good image

01:00:47.680 --> 01:00:52.594
of the importance of these
two different branches.

01:00:52.594 --> 01:00:54.260
And we now know that
the North Icelandic

01:00:54.260 --> 01:00:56.370
Jet is something that's
there all year round,

01:00:56.370 --> 01:00:58.720
and it brings a significant
quantity of water.

01:00:58.720 --> 01:01:01.200
The question now is
where does it come from?

01:01:01.200 --> 01:01:02.890
And that's still
an open question.

01:01:02.890 --> 01:01:03.870
We don't really know.

01:01:03.870 --> 01:01:07.220
One hypothesis is that that
warm water that actually comes

01:01:07.220 --> 01:01:10.170
in north of Iceland, it
kind of spreads out here

01:01:10.170 --> 01:01:13.310
into the Iceland Sea, and
it's subject to very, very

01:01:13.310 --> 01:01:17.620
cold intense winter conditions,
and it sinks directly here

01:01:17.620 --> 01:01:20.584
and flows directly back
towards the Strait.

01:01:20.584 --> 01:01:22.750
The reason we think that
is because, actually, we've

01:01:22.750 --> 01:01:24.150
followed the North
Icelandic Jet upstream

01:01:24.150 --> 01:01:25.430
and followed that fingerprint.

01:01:25.430 --> 01:01:28.460
It eventually just
peters out around here.

01:01:28.460 --> 01:01:30.010
Kind of comes from nowhere.

01:01:30.010 --> 01:01:32.550
But it was also, kind of,
comes from a very large body

01:01:32.550 --> 01:01:33.192
of dense water.

01:01:33.192 --> 01:01:34.900
So we think there's
a kind of smoking gun

01:01:34.900 --> 01:01:36.750
there about where
that water is formed.

01:01:36.750 --> 01:01:38.360
But we don't know.

01:01:38.360 --> 01:01:40.840
The next big project is heading
out into the Iceland Sea

01:01:40.840 --> 01:01:43.440
to work out whether we can find
exactly where that water is

01:01:43.440 --> 01:01:45.904
coming from.

01:01:45.904 --> 01:01:47.320
Taking a step out
again, you know,

01:01:47.320 --> 01:01:49.940
now we kind of have this
slightly more sophisticated

01:01:49.940 --> 01:01:53.120
picture of where the overflow
water is coming from.

01:01:53.120 --> 01:01:54.940
This region here
in the Iceland Sea

01:01:54.940 --> 01:01:57.570
could be important, this region
here where making dense water

01:01:57.570 --> 01:01:58.840
could be important.

01:01:58.840 --> 01:02:00.416
There are also
other possibilities,

01:02:00.416 --> 01:02:02.290
things that we may not
have thought about yet

01:02:02.290 --> 01:02:04.748
because we haven't been able
to go out there and measure it

01:02:04.748 --> 01:02:06.677
often enough.

01:02:06.677 --> 01:02:09.010
But this all kind of brings
us back to the central point

01:02:09.010 --> 01:02:11.732
is that if we can't make this
dense water somewhere, then

01:02:11.732 --> 01:02:13.440
we can't bring the
warm water northwards.

01:02:13.440 --> 01:02:16.765
And that's going to change the
climate of the Northern Europe

01:02:16.765 --> 01:02:17.265
regions.

01:02:19.860 --> 01:02:22.160
So, some key questions
going forward.

01:02:22.160 --> 01:02:24.490
You know, where is this
North Icelandic Jet formed?

01:02:24.490 --> 01:02:30.340
How is it formed and
how often is it formed?

01:02:30.340 --> 01:02:32.480
Do the two branches
compensate for each other?

01:02:32.480 --> 01:02:34.990
If, under some
climate scenario, we

01:02:34.990 --> 01:02:37.710
have an increase in wind
in a particular area,

01:02:37.710 --> 01:02:40.770
sea ice retreated
back somewhere,

01:02:40.770 --> 01:02:43.180
would one of these
currents be able to pick up

01:02:43.180 --> 01:02:46.305
the slack from the other one
if the other one was weakening?

01:02:46.305 --> 01:02:48.450
Would the other one be
able to intensify in order

01:02:48.450 --> 01:02:50.260
to pick up the slack?

01:02:50.260 --> 01:02:51.600
It's an open question.

01:02:51.600 --> 01:02:53.340
And how sensitive
is the whole system?

01:02:53.340 --> 01:02:56.311
We know in the past that
this whole thermohaline,

01:02:56.311 --> 01:02:58.060
this whole circulation,
the North Atlantic

01:02:58.060 --> 01:03:00.917
shut down various glacial
periods in the past.

01:03:00.917 --> 01:03:03.250
Is that something that could
happen under climate change

01:03:03.250 --> 01:03:05.916
scenarios, or is the
system robust enough

01:03:05.916 --> 01:03:07.290
under the kind of
changes that it

01:03:07.290 --> 01:03:09.610
will see to actually be
able to sustain itself

01:03:09.610 --> 01:03:13.150
and be able to keep bringing
this warm water northwards?

01:03:13.150 --> 01:03:14.990
I turn to this picture.

01:03:14.990 --> 01:03:17.790
We've been asking the question
of how this warm water flows

01:03:17.790 --> 01:03:20.310
North, and it's because we can
exchange with this deep water

01:03:20.310 --> 01:03:21.050
that flows South.

01:03:21.050 --> 01:03:24.070
And as it cascades down
to 2000, 3000 meters,

01:03:24.070 --> 01:03:26.060
it makes it's way
southwards and it hugs

01:03:26.060 --> 01:03:26.935
the east coast of the states.

01:03:26.935 --> 01:03:28.810
It actually ends up
directly underneath where

01:03:28.810 --> 01:03:30.400
it started in the Gulf Stream.

01:03:30.400 --> 01:03:32.170
So it kind of goes
nowhere eventually,

01:03:32.170 --> 01:03:33.810
it just gets deeper.

01:03:33.810 --> 01:03:38.196
And ends up heading all the way
down southwards past Brazil.

01:03:38.196 --> 01:03:39.820
And, you know, there's
a kind of couple

01:03:39.820 --> 01:03:43.140
of things I wanted to say about
this larger scale circulation.

01:03:43.140 --> 01:03:45.600
Was that there's been
some effort for a while

01:03:45.600 --> 01:03:49.460
to actually monitor that
large scale circulation down

01:03:49.460 --> 01:03:50.590
off the coast of Florida.

01:03:50.590 --> 01:03:53.500
A large mooring
array out here called

01:03:53.500 --> 01:03:56.940
the rapid array which is trying
to measure the warm water

01:03:56.940 --> 01:03:58.950
outflow and the
cold water inflow

01:03:58.950 --> 01:04:01.910
and try to make some estimates
of how robust the system is,

01:04:01.910 --> 01:04:05.880
how the heat exchange is
actually changing over time.

01:04:05.880 --> 01:04:09.640
And lest we forget this whole
thing is tied into a larger

01:04:09.640 --> 01:04:11.460
system that goes planet wide.

01:04:11.460 --> 01:04:13.560
We've been talking
about this warm water

01:04:13.560 --> 01:04:17.712
outflow, the cold water
exchange coming back South.

01:04:17.712 --> 01:04:19.812
But this whole thing is
tied into a complex series

01:04:19.812 --> 01:04:21.520
of currents that extend
around the globe.

01:04:21.520 --> 01:04:24.770
How could one, how could
changes in one of these branches

01:04:24.770 --> 01:04:28.325
impact onwards throughout
that entire system.

01:04:28.325 --> 01:04:30.950
So that's the, kind of, thought
I wanted to leave you on today.

01:04:30.950 --> 01:04:32.616
Thank you very much
for having me speak.

01:04:32.616 --> 01:04:33.540
It's been a pleasure.

