01:09:06.569 --> 01:09:09.420
Like, I'm kind of curious.

01:09:09.420 --> 01:09:13.290
-Yeah, it's a little hard.

01:09:13.290 --> 01:09:16.520
You've got water
falling through water,

01:09:16.520 --> 01:09:20.032
so it's not actually something
you can take a picture of.

01:09:20.032 --> 01:09:22.490
We know that they exist because
you can go down and measure

01:09:22.490 --> 01:09:23.670
the speed of the water.

01:09:23.670 --> 01:09:26.035
And you know that the water
above it's largely stagnant,

01:09:26.035 --> 01:09:27.410
and then this
layer on the bottom

01:09:27.410 --> 01:09:30.090
is sliding down
to the deep water.

01:09:30.090 --> 01:09:32.649
But we're talking about
ocean currents, which

01:09:32.649 --> 01:09:35.540
aren't necessarily falling
at the rate of water

01:09:35.540 --> 01:09:36.590
from a waterfall.

01:09:36.590 --> 01:09:39.589
Typically these currents,
at their strongest velocity,

01:09:39.589 --> 01:09:43.979
is maybe moving, upstream
of the Strait, maybe 10,

01:09:43.979 --> 01:09:47.186
20 centimeters a second.

01:09:47.186 --> 01:09:48.560
Actually, in the
overflow itself,

01:09:48.560 --> 01:09:50.160
you might get up to
like a meter a second,

01:09:50.160 --> 01:09:51.069
or something like that.

01:09:51.069 --> 01:09:52.818
The Gulf Stream's a
particularly fast one,

01:09:52.818 --> 01:09:54.660
that can go at least
a meter a second.

01:09:54.660 --> 01:09:59.840
But, yeah, it's a little
hard to visualize explicitly.

01:09:59.840 --> 01:10:02.290
You kind of have to-- with
all of physical oceanography,

01:10:02.290 --> 01:10:04.373
I think part of the beauty
of it, a friend of mine

01:10:04.373 --> 01:10:07.954
said this, was that you
can't see below the waves,

01:10:07.954 --> 01:10:09.370
and so a lot of
what we have to do

01:10:09.370 --> 01:10:12.360
is throw our imaginations
down into the deep

01:10:12.360 --> 01:10:14.297
to see these things.

