01:10:38.360 --> 01:10:39.770
-Also a question for Ben.

01:10:39.770 --> 01:10:41.420
You were talking a
little bit about how

01:10:41.420 --> 01:10:42.980
what you're looking
at specifically

01:10:42.980 --> 01:10:45.431
is related to global
ocean circulation.

01:10:45.431 --> 01:10:47.180
And I was wondering,
thinking about, like,

01:10:47.180 --> 01:10:49.470
North Atlantic deep water
formation, and stuff like that.

01:10:49.470 --> 01:10:51.070
Looking forwards
with climate change,

01:10:51.070 --> 01:10:54.540
what do you know or think
about possible changes

01:10:54.540 --> 01:10:57.360
in that circulation and whether
the specific currents you're

01:10:57.360 --> 01:10:59.310
looking at could
have some effect,

01:10:59.310 --> 01:11:00.690
and how do they change too?

01:11:00.690 --> 01:11:02.610
-Yeah, absolutely.

01:11:02.610 --> 01:11:06.360
We know from the geological
record that in the past

01:11:06.360 --> 01:11:08.620
that circulation has
largely shut off,

01:11:08.620 --> 01:11:10.000
or it has become
shallower, or it

01:11:10.000 --> 01:11:11.560
has moved to a different
part the North Atlantic,

01:11:11.560 --> 01:11:13.720
all of which would
affect how much heat we

01:11:13.720 --> 01:11:15.220
can get northwards.

01:11:15.220 --> 01:11:17.850
One of the major concerns
in the climate change

01:11:17.850 --> 01:11:20.700
is melting of the
Greenland ice sheet.

01:11:20.700 --> 01:11:22.190
You melt more fresh
water, you dump

01:11:22.190 --> 01:11:24.130
that out into the ocean,
and all of a sudden

01:11:24.130 --> 01:11:28.480
you've got this fresh, really
light cap on the water that

01:11:28.480 --> 01:11:30.590
is really hard for
the winds to cool

01:11:30.590 --> 01:11:32.080
down enough to make it sink.

01:11:32.080 --> 01:11:34.840
So you're basically shutting
off, and making little cap

01:11:34.840 --> 01:11:39.210
on the surface which shuts off
this dense water formation.

01:11:39.210 --> 01:11:42.820
It's not entirely clear
if that is happening

01:11:42.820 --> 01:11:44.599
or will be important.

01:11:44.599 --> 01:11:46.390
As I was showing, a
lot of that fresh water

01:11:46.390 --> 01:11:49.630
is flushed out along
the shelf of Greenland.

01:11:49.630 --> 01:11:51.150
It's going to be
important to know

01:11:51.150 --> 01:11:53.910
if we can get that fresh
water off the shelf

01:11:53.910 --> 01:11:56.740
and into the open ocean regions
where this dense water is

01:11:56.740 --> 01:11:57.850
being formed.

01:11:57.850 --> 01:12:00.410
That's going to be important.

01:12:00.410 --> 01:12:02.955
Another thing is if we
have retreating sea ice.

01:12:02.955 --> 01:12:05.580
The edge of the sea ice is often
where a lot of the dense water

01:12:05.580 --> 01:12:07.830
is made because you have
these winds coming off

01:12:07.830 --> 01:12:11.180
the edge of it, they're very
cold and they're very dry.

01:12:11.180 --> 01:12:13.850
So you can take both moisture
and heat out, both of which

01:12:13.850 --> 01:12:15.490
make the water denser.

01:12:15.490 --> 01:12:18.550
And so the sea
ice edge positions

01:12:18.550 --> 01:12:20.400
are kind of important
parameter in knowing

01:12:20.400 --> 01:12:22.608
where the dense water is
going to form, specifically.

01:12:22.608 --> 01:12:25.060
So if that sea ice keeps
retreating or changing

01:12:25.060 --> 01:12:29.420
its positions, it may change
where we form the deep water.

01:12:29.420 --> 01:12:31.720
Just as, you know, what
we've seen currently

01:12:31.720 --> 01:12:34.680
there's been no evidence so
far, no categoric evidence

01:12:34.680 --> 01:12:38.676
that we've seen a
slowdown in that system.

01:12:38.676 --> 01:12:41.130
But we also know that it
has happened in the past

01:12:41.130 --> 01:12:42.280
and it could happen again.

01:12:42.280 --> 01:12:44.576
And we have lots of hypothesis
for how it might change.

01:12:50.490 --> 01:12:52.840
-My question is for Lydia.

01:12:52.840 --> 01:12:56.040
One of the really
mind blowing things

01:12:56.040 --> 01:13:00.470
that has come to my attention
as we've started here

01:13:00.470 --> 01:13:04.420
at the Institute to think about
our year focused on oceans

01:13:04.420 --> 01:13:06.520
is the question
that you addressed,

01:13:06.520 --> 01:13:09.080
where do oceans come from?

01:13:09.080 --> 01:13:13.040
Because at first I thought
